'''Justin McCarthy''' (22 November 1830 – 24 April 1912) was an [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalist]] and Liberal historian, novelist and politician. He was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) from 1879 to 1900, taking his seat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]].

==Early life==
McCarthy was born in [[Cork (city)|Cork City, Cork]], and was educated there. He began his career as a journalist, aged 18, in Cork. From 1853 to 1859 he was in [[Liverpool]], on the staff of the ''[[Northern Daily Times]]''. In March 1855, he married Charlotte Ailman. In 1860 he moved to London, as parliamentary reporter to ''[[The Morning Star (19th century U.K. newspaper)|The Morning Star]]'', of which he became editor in 1864. He gave up his post in 1868, and, after a lecturing tour in the United States, joined the staff of the ''[[The_Daily_News_(UK)|Daily News]]'' as leader-writer in 1870. In this capacity he became one of the most useful and respected upholders of the liberal politics of the time. He lectured again in America in 1870–71, and again in 1886–87. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

==Political career==
[[File:Justin McCarthy Vanity Fair 1885-05-23.jpg|left|thumb|160px|McCarthy caricatured by [[Leslie Ward|Spy]] in [[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]], 1885]]
McCarthy was first elected to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] at a by-election on 4 April 1879, when he was returned unopposed as a [[Home Rule League]] MP for [[Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|County Longford]].<ref name="walker-1801-1922">{{cite book|title=Parliamentary election results in Ireland 1801–1922|editor=Brian M. Walker|publisher=Royal Irish Academy|location=Dublin|year=1978|isbn=0-901714-12-7|page=122}}</ref> He was re-elected unopposed as a Parnellite Home Ruler in [[United Kingdom general election, 1880|1880]],<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 125</ref> and when the two-seat Longford constituency was split into two divisions under the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885|Redistribution of Seats Act]], he was elected as an [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] member for the new single-seat [[North Longford (UK Parliament constituency)|Northern division of Longford]]. His sole opponent, a Conservative, won only 6% of the votes.<ref>Walker, op. cit., pg. 134</ref>

At the [[United Kingdom general election, 1886|1886 general election]], he was returned unopposed in North Longford,<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 140</ref> but had also stood in [[Londonderry City (UK Parliament constituency)|Londonderry City]], where he was declared to have lost to the [[Irish Unionist Alliance|Unionist]] candidate by the narrow margin of 1778 votes to 1781.<ref>Walker, op. cit., pg. 139</ref> However, the result was later overturned on peition, and McCarthy opted to sit for Derry City. During the divorce controversy surrounding [[Charles Stewart Parnell]] in November 1890, the British Prime Minister [[William Ewart Gladstone|Gladstone]] expressed a warning, given to Justin McCarthy as intermediary, that if Parnell retained leadership of the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]] it would mean the loss of the next election, the end of their alliance and Home Rule. When the annual party leadership election meeting was called later that month, this threat was somehow not conveyed to the members, who re-elected Parnell leader of the Party. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

After a further historical meeting of the Irish Party MPs early December, Parnell refused to retire, and the Party divided. McCarthy became chairman of the Anti-Parnellite group, or the [[Irish National Federation]] for a year in 1891–1892; but his nationalism was of a temperate and orderly kind, and though his personal distinction singled him out for the chairmanship during the party dissensions of this period, he was in no active sense the political leader. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

At the [[United Kingdom general election, 1892|1892 general election]], McCarthy again stood both in North Longford and in Derry City. In each seat there was a two-way contest between the [[Anti-Parnellite]] McCarthy and a Unionist candidate, but the narrow Unionist victory in Derry (by 1986 votes to 1960) was not overturned, and McCarthy sat for North Longford, where he had won over 93% of the votes.<ref>Walker, op. cit., page 147</ref> He was returned unopposed for North Longford in [[United Kingdom general election, 1895|1895]], and stood down from Parliament at the [[United Kingdom general election, 1900|1900 general election]].

==Writing==
It has been claimed that McCarthy's true vocation was literature.<ref>*{{Citation|first=George|last=Wilman|title=Sketches of living celebrities|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=alwBAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA68|year=1882|publisher=Griffith and Farran|location=London|pages=68–76|chapter=Justin McCarthy}}</ref> His earliest publications were novels, some of which, such as ''A Fair Saxon'' (1873), ''Dear Lady Disdain'' (1875), ''Miss Misanthrope'' (1878), ''Donna Quixote'' (1879), attained considerable popularity. His most important work is his ''History of Our Own Times'' (vols. i.iv., 1879–1880; vol. v., 1897), which treats of the period between [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]]'s accession and her [[Diamond Jubilee]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCarthy |first= Justin |author-link= Justin_McCarthy_(1830–1912) |title= A History of Our Own Times: From the Accession of Queen Victoria to the General Elections of 1880 |publisher=  Chatto & Windus |place= London  |year= 1880 |volume = I |page= |url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.210308 |accessdate= 15 March 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}; {{cite book |last=McCarthy |first= Justin |author-link= Justin_McCarthy_(1830–1912) |title= A History of Our Own Times: From the Accession of Queen Victoria to the General Elections of 1880 |publisher=  Chatto & Windus |place= London  |year= 1881 |volume = II |page= |url= https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.210309/2015.210309.A-History#page/n5/mode/2up |accessdate= 15 March 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}; {{cite book |last=McCarthy |first= Justin |author-link= Justin_McCarthy_(1830–1912) |title= A History of Our Own Times: From the Accession of Queen Victoria to the General Elections of 1880 |publisher=  Chatto & Windus |place= London  |year= 1881 |volume = III |page= |url= https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.210310/2015.210310.A-History#page/n5/mode/2up |accessdate= 15 March 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}; {{cite book |last=McCarthy |first= Justin |author-link= Justin_McCarthy_(1830–1912) |title= A History of Our Own Times: From the Accession of Queen Victoria to the General Elections of 1880 |publisher=  Chatto & Windus |place= London  |year= 1881 |volume = IV |page= |url= https://archive.org/stream/in.ernet.dli.2015.210311/2015.210311.A-History#page/n5/mode/2up |accessdate= 15 March 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}</ref> He began a ''History of the Four Georges'' (1884–1901); the latter half was written by his son, [[Justin Huntly McCarthy]]. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

He also collaborated on three novels with [[Rosa Campbell Praed]]: ''The Right Honourable'' (1886), ''The Rebel Rose'' (issued anonymously in 1888 but appeared in their joint names in two later editions under the title, ''The Rival Princess''), and ''The Ladies' Gallery'' (1888). They also collaborated on ''The Grey River'', a book on the Thames, which was illustrated with etchings by [[Mortimer Menpes]]. He wrote ''The Story of Gladstone'' (1904), a somewhat uncritical biography of William Ewart Gladstone. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}

==Family life==
McCarthy married in 1855, they had a son [[Justin Huntly McCarthy]] born in 1859 who also became a Member of Parliament, and they had a daughter Charlotte born in 1872. McCarthy died in Folkestone, Kent, England on 24 April 1912, aged 81.<ref name="times">{{cite web |title=Mr. Justin McCarthy |journal= Times |place=London, England |date= 26 April 1912 |volume= 11 |publisher=The Times Digital Archive|accessdate= 31 May 2015}}</ref>

