{{nihongo|'''''Karyaku'''''|嘉暦}}, also romanized as '''Kareki''', was a {{nihongo|[[Japanese era name]]|年号,|''nengō'',|lit. "year name"}} after ''[[Shōchū (era)|Shōchū]]'' and before ''[[Gentoku]].''  This period spanned the years from April 1326 through August 1329.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "''Karyaku''" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', p. 483|page=483}}; n.b., Louis-Frédéric is pseudonym of Louis-Frédéric Nussbaum, ''see'' [http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Authority File] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120524174828/http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 |date=2012-05-24 }}.</ref> The reigning Emperor was {{nihongo|[[Emperor Go-Daigo|Go-Daigo]]''-tennō''|後醍醐天皇}}.<ref>Titsingh, Isaac. (1834). ''Annales des empereurs du Japon'', pp. 278-281; Varley, H. Paul. (1980). ''Jinnō Shōtōki.'' pp. 239-241.</ref>

==Change of era==
* '''1326''' {{nihongo|''Karyaku gannen''|嘉暦元年}}: The new era name was created to mark an event or series of events. The previous era ended and the new one commenced in ''Shōchū'' 3.

==Events of the ''Karyaku'' era==
* '''March 8, 1327''' (''Karyaku 2, 14th day of the 2nd month'')<!-- NengoCalc 嘉暦二年二月十四日  -->: There is a total eclipse of the moon.<ref>Xu, Zhentao ''et al.'' (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=9JatFvikiwQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=East-Asian+Archaeoastronomy:+Historical+Records+of+Astronomical+Observations+of+China,+Japan+and+Korea&client=firefox-a#PPA97,M1  ''East-Asian Archaeoastronomy: Historical Records of Astronomical Observations of China, Japan and Korea, '' p. 97.]</ref>

