'''Khirbat Faynan''', also known as '''Phaino''', is an [[archaeological site]] in [[Wadi Faynan]], southern [[Jordan]]. Located at the confluence of Wadi Dana and Wadi Ghuwayr, the settlement was occupied from the early [[Bronze Age]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newswatch.nationalgeographic.com/2012/05/29/excavations-at-the-site-of-an-ancient-techno-revolution/|title=Excavations at the Site of an Ancient Techno-Revolution|last=Ward|first=Lauren|date=2012-05-29|website=National Geographic|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref> and has been identified with the biblical [[Punon]], one of the [[stations of the Exodus]]. In the [[Ancient Rome|Roman]]-[[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] period, it was the centre of the area's extensive [[copper mining]] complex, the largest in the [[Southern Levant]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.world-archaeology.com/features/wadi-faynan-copper-mine.htm|title=Wadi Faynan, Copper Mine|last=|first=|date=2005-09-07|work=|newspaper=World Archaeology|issue=13|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-09|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Novo|first=Alexandre|last2=Vincent|first2=Matthew L.|last3=Levy|first3=Thomas E.|date=2012-08-29|title=Geophysical Surveys at Khirbat Faynan, an Ancient Mound Site in Southern Jordan|url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/ijge/2012/432823/|journal=International Journal of Geophysics|language=en|volume=2012|pages=1–8|doi=10.1155/2012/432823|issn=1687-885X}}</ref>

