The '''Reşvan''', '''Reşwan''' or '''Rişvan tribe''' is a [[Kurds|Kurdish]] tribe, native to the [[Adıyaman]], [[Gaziantep]], [[Kahramanmaraş]] and [[Malatya]] areas.<ref name="aksiyon" /> Notably they reside [[Kahta|Kahta district]] of [[Adıyaman Province]], the northern part of [[Konya Province]] and southern part of [[Ankara Province]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Rişvan Aşireti’nden Vali Ramazan Sodan’a Ziyaret|url=http://www.kahtaolay.com/?HaberID=1822|accessdate=29 March 2015|date=9 June 2012|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=De midtanatolske kurdere - en ufortalt historie|url=http://jiyan.dk/2011/08/de-midtanatolske-kurdere-en-ufortalt-historie/|accessdate=29 March 2015|agency=Jiyan.dk|date=16 August 2011|language=Danish}}</ref> Some Reşvan Kurds live in [[Sivas]], [[Qazvin]] (Iran) and [[Rojava|Rojava (Syrian Kurdistan)]] as well.<ref name="suatdede" />
==History== Experts suggest that the name Reşvan is a compound of ''reş'' ("black") and the Kurdish plural form ''-ân''.<ref name="suatdede" /> The name of the tribe was recorded in the ''[[defter]]'' (tax register) back in 1519, when Sultan [[Selim I]] conquered Malatya and Kahta. The tribe was also mentioned in 1524 and 1536, although its numbers were not recorded. The tribe was like all other Kurdish tribes nomadic before the [[Ottoman Empire]] managed to sedentarize them, as part of the [[Tanzimat]]. The first attempt to sedentarize the tribe took place in 1830 and the process continued through [[Atatürk's Reforms]] (about 1923). During the sedentarization the Reşvan tribe was one of the biggest and most influential Kurdish tribes.<ref name="suatdede" >{{cite journal|last1=Dede|first1=Suat|title=From nomadism to sedentary life in Central Anatolia: The case of the Risvan tribe (1830 - 1932)|date=December 2011|pages=120|url=http://www.thesis.bilkent.edu.tr/0005059.pdf|accessdate=29 March 2015}}</ref>
In the 1800s, some Kurds from the tribe moved to or were deported to [[Central Anatolia]], where they today reside in many villages around [[Cihanbeyli]], [[Haymana]], [[Boztepe, Kırşehir|Boztepe]] and [[Kulu, Konya|Kulu]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cihanbeyli - Index Anatolicus|url=http://www.nisanyanmap.com/?y=&t=Cihanbeyli&lv=1&u=1&ua=0|publisher=Index Anatolicus|accessdate=29 March 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Haymana - Index Anatolicus|url=http://www.nisanyanmap.com/?y=&t=Haymana&lv=1&srt=x&u=1&ua=0|publisher=Index Anatolicus|accessdate=29 March 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Boztepe - Index Anatolicus|url=http://www.nisanyanmap.com/?y=&t=Boztepe&lv=1&srt=x&u=1&ua=0|publisher=Index Anatolicus|accessdate=29 March 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kulu - Index Anatolicus|url=http://www.nisanyanmap.com/?y=&t=Kulu&lv=1&srt=x&u=1&ua=0|publisher=Index Anatolicus|accessdate=29 March 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref> A 1859 document shows that about 500 households of the tribe lived in Haymana, [[Ankara]], being sedentarized in 43 villages.<ref name="suatdede" />
During the 1890s, the leader of the tribe Yakup Ragıp from [[Besni]] protected [[Armenians]] from Ottoman massacres.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Şemsa Özar, Nesrin Uçarlar, Osman Aytar|title=From past to present a paramilitary organization in Turkey|date=December 2013|isbn=978-6055458195|page=26|url=http://dealingwiththepast.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Disa-Paramilitary.pdf|accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref>
==Politics and elections== The majority of the tribe are [[Sunni Muslims]] (and a minority [[Alevi]]), inhabiting [[Adıyaman]], [[Kahramanmaraş]] and [[Malatya]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Reswan-stammen fra Konya|url=http://jiyan.dk/2011/08/reswan-stammen-fra-konya-oprindeligt-alevi/|publisher=Jiyan.dk|accessdate=29 March 2015|language=Danish|date=17 August 2011}}</ref> and tend to be conservative. The tribe mainly voted for the conservative [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|AKP]]<ref name="aksiyon" >{{cite news|title=Aşiret oyları cepte değil|url=http://www.aksiyon.com.tr/siyaset/asiret-oylari-cepte-degil_509798|publisher=Aksiyon|accessdate=29 March 2015|date=1 March 2004}}</ref> until 2014, when the well-known Reşvan Kurdish politician [[Dengir Mir Mehmet Fırat]] resigned from AKP and decided to run for the pro-Kurdish [[Peoples' Democratic Party (Turkey)|Peoples' Democratic Party]] (HDP) in the local election in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Failure of pro-Kurdish HDP to enter Parliament could spell trouble|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/national_failure-of-pro-kurdish-hdp-to-enter-parliament-could-spell-trouble_376530.html|website=Today's Zaman|accessdate=29 March 2015|date=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Kurdish leaders to run in elections despite HDP’s two-term limit|url=http://politics.bgnnews.com/pro-kurdish-leaders-to-run-in-elections-despite-hdps-two-term-limit-haberi/3847|accessdate=29 March 2015|agency=26 February 2015}}</ref> The leaders of the tribe decided to vote for HDP in the [[Turkish general election, June 2015|general election]] in June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=HDP aşiretleri nasıl ikna etti?|url=http://www.radikal.com.tr/politika/hdp_asiretleri_nasil_ikna_etti-1354021|accessdate=5 June 2015|agency=Radikal|date=11 May 2015|language=Turkish}}</ref>
