:''For a list of groups involved in the conflict, see [[Directory of the Northern Ireland Troubles]]'' :''For a chronology of the peace process, see [[Northern Ireland peace process]]'' {{dynamiclist}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}} {{Campaignbox Northern Ireland Troubles|state=expanded}} This article lists the major violent and political incidents during the [[Troubles]], [[Northern Ireland peace process|peace process]], and a [[Dissident Irish Republican campaign|dissident campaign]] in [[Northern Ireland]], from the late 1960s until the present day. The Troubles was a period of conflict in Northern Ireland involving [[Irish republicanism|republican]] and [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] [[paramilitary|paramilitaries]], the [[Law enforcement in the United Kingdom|British security forces]], and civil rights groups. The Troubles is usually dated from the riots of 1968 through the [[Good Friday Agreement]] of 1998.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch68.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1968], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref><ref>Aughey, Arthur. ''The Politics of Northern Ireland: Beyond the Belfast Agreement'', page 7; {{ISBN|978-0-415-32788-6}}</ref><ref name="Ireland 1999, page 221">[[Jack Holland (writer)|Holland, Jack]]. "The troubles were over, but the killing continued. Some of the heirs to Ireland's violent traditions refused to give up their inheritance", ''Hope against History: The Course of Conflict in Northern Ireland''. Henry Holt & Company, 1999, page 221; {{ISBN|0-8050-6087-1}}</ref><ref name="Northern Ireland Conflict' page 250">Gillespie, Gordon. ''Historical Dictionary of the Northern Ireland Conflict'', page 250; {{ISBN|978-0-8108-5583-0}}</ref> However, sporadic violence continued after this point. Those that continued violence past this point are referred to as [[Dissident republican]]s and Loyalists in the Dissident Irish Republican Campaign. The Troubles 1968-1998, claimed roughly 3500 lives while the Dissident Irish Republican Campaign 1998–present, has claimed around 150 lives.<ref>O'Rourke, Liam. [http://www.thevacuum.org.uk/issues/issues0120/issue08/is08artstadan.html Statistics Of Danger], volume 8.</ref>
==Prior to 1960== Since [[Partition of Ireland|partition]], the [[Irish Republican Army (1922–69)|IRA]] had started a number of military operations in [[Northern Ireland]] designed at bringing about their goal of a [[United Ireland]]. The intensity of this activity increased towards the end of 1941, where the IRA decided to step up its [[Northern Campaign (Irish Republican Army)|campaign of attacks in Northern Ireland]].<ref name=cain1800>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch1800-1967.htm CAIN: Chronology of Key Events in Irish History, 1800 to 1967; section 1941 and onwards], cain.ulst.ac.uk; accessed 13 April 2018.</ref> In response to this activity the Unionist authorities under [[J. M. Andrews|John Miller Andrews]] introduced internment and using provisions of the [[Emergency Powers Act (Northern Ireland) 1926|Emergency Powers Act]], instituted increasingly restrictive policies in Northern Ireland. This pattern of paramilitary violence, followed by increasingly restrictive measures on the behalf of the authorities came to define the run-up to the Troubles.
==1960–1969== Since 1964, [[Northern Ireland civil-rights movement (1960s)|civil rights activists]] had been protesting against the discrimination against [[Irish Catholic|Catholics]] and [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalists]] by the [[Ulster Protestant]] and [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]] [[government of Northern Ireland]]. The civil rights movement called for: '[[one man, one vote]]'; the end to [[Gerrymandering|gerrymandered]] electoral boundaries; the end to discrimination in employment and in the allocation of public housing; repeal of the [[Civil Authorities (Special Powers) Act (Northern Ireland) 1922|Special Powers Act]]; and the disbanding of the [[Ulster Special Constabulary]].<ref name=cain1800/>
==Key== {|"floatright" style="background:#ffd;" |- |Political action or event |- style="background:#eef;" |Political or civil violence |- style="background:#fee;" |Paramilitary killing, bombing or assassination attempt |}
===1966=== {|"floatright" style="background:#ffd;" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| April |[[Ulster loyalism|Loyalists]] led by [[Ian Paisley]], a Protestant preacher, founded the [[Ulster Constitution Defence Committee]] (UCDC) to oppose the civil rights movement. It set up a paramilitary-style wing called the [[Ulster Protestant Volunteers]] (UPV).<ref name=cain1800/> |- |valign="top"| 21 May |A loyalist group calling itself the [[Ulster Volunteer Force]] (UVF) issued a statement declaring war on the [[Irish Republican Army (1922–1969)|Irish Republican Army]] (IRA). The group claimed to be composed of "heavily armed Protestants dedicated to this cause".<ref>See Nelson, Sarah. "Ulster's Uncertain Defenders: Protestant Political Paramilitary and Community Groups and the Northern Ireland Conflict", p. 61, Belfast: Appletree Press, 1984.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> At the time, the IRA was not engaged in armed action, and [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalists]] were marking the 50th anniversary of the [[Easter Rising]]. Some [[Unionism in Ireland|unionists]] warned "that a revival of the IRA was imminent".<ref name=cain1800/> |- style="background:#fee;" |valign="top" | May–June |The UVF carried out three attacks on Catholics in Belfast. In the first, a Protestant civilian (Matilda Gould) died when UVF members tried to firebomb the Catholic-owned pub beside her house but accidentally struck her home. In the second, a Catholic civilian (John Patrick Scullion) was shot dead as he walked home. In the third, the UVF opened fire on three Catholic civilians as they left a pub, killing one (Peter Ward, a native of the Republic of Ireland) and wounding the other two.<ref name=cain1800/> |}
===1968=== {|"floatright" style="background:#ffd;" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 20 June |Civil rights activists (including [[Parliament Buildings (Northern Ireland)|Stormont]] MP [[Austin Currie]]) protested against discrimination in the allocation of housing by illegally occupying a house in [[Caledon, County Tyrone]]. An unmarried Protestant woman (the secretary of a local [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) politician) had been given the house ahead of Catholic families with children. The protesters were forcibly removed by the [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]] (RUC).<ref name=cain68>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch68.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – 1968]. ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 24 August |Northern Ireland's first civil rights march was held. Many more marches would be held over the following year. Loyalists attacked some of the marches and organized counter-demonstrations to get the marches banned.<ref name=cain68/> |- |valign="top"| 5 October |A [[Northern Ireland Civil Rights Association]] march was to take place in [[Derry]]. When the loyalist [[Apprentice Boys of Derry|Apprentice Boys]] announced its intention to hold a march at the same place and time, the Government banned all marches taking place that day. When civil rights activists defied the ban, RUC officers surrounded the marchers and beat them indiscriminately and without provocation.<ref name=derrymarch>{{cite web|title=The Derry March: Main events of the day|author=Martin Melaugh|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/derry/events.htm|publisher=[[Conflict Archive on the Internet]] (CAIN)|accessdate=16 February 2008}}</ref> Over 100 people were injured, including a number of MPs.<ref name=derrymarch/> This sparked two days of serious rioting in Derry between Republicans and the RUC.<ref name=cain68/> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 9 October |About 2,000 students from [[Queen's University Belfast]] tried to march to [[Belfast City Hall]] in protest against [[police brutality]] on 5 October in Derry. The march was blocked by loyalists led by Ian Paisley. After the demonstration, a student civil rights group—[[People's Democracy (Ireland)|People's Democracy]]—was formed.<ref name=cain68/> |}
===1969=== {|"floatright" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 4 January |A People's Democracy march between Belfast and Derry was repeatedly attacked by loyalists. At [[Burntollet]] it was ambushed by 200 loyalists and off-duty police (RUC) officers armed with iron bars, bricks and bottles. The marchers claimed that police did little to protect them. When the march arrived in Derry it was broken up by the RUC, which sparked serious rioting between Irish nationalists and the RUC.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Jan A Chronology of the Conflict – January 1969] ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> That night, RUC officers went on a rampage in the [[Bogside]] area of Derry; attacking Catholic homes, attacking and threatening residents, and hurling sectarian abuse.<ref name=burntollet>Bowes Egan and Vincent McCormack. ''[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/events/pdmarch/egan.htm Burntollet]''. L.R.S. Publishers, 1969. Reproduced on CAIN; retrieved 12 June 2013.</ref> Residents then sealed off the Bogside with barricades to keep the police out, creating "[[Free Derry]]". |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| March–April |The loyalists intended to bring down the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]], [[Terence O'Neill, Baron O'Neill of the Maine|Terence O'Neill]], who had promised some concessions to the civil rights movement. To this end, Members of the loyalist UVF and UPV bombed water and electricity installations in Northern Ireland, in deceitful [[false flag]] attacks, blaming them on the dormant IRA and on elements of the civil rights movement. There were six bombings and all were widely blamed on the IRA. As a response, British soldiers were sent to guard installations. Despite this, Loyalist-Unionist support for O'Neill continued to wane, and on 28 April he resigned as Prime Minister.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1969] ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 17 April |People's Democracy activist [[Bernadette Devlin]] was the youngest woman ever elected to Westminster, a record which stood until [[Mhairi Black]]'s election in 2015. |- |valign="top"| 19 April |During clashes with civil rights marchers in Derry, RUC officers entered the house of an uninvolved Catholic civilian, Samuel Devenny, and beat him, along with two of his daughters.<ref name=cain1969>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm|title=Chronology of the Conflict: 1969|publisher=[[Conflict Archive on the Internet]] (CAIN)|accessdate=12 June 2013}}</ref> One of the daughters was beaten unconscious as she lay recovering from surgery.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/issues/police/ombudsman/po041001devenny.pdf Police Ombudsman statement on Devenny investigation (4 October 2001)]. [[Conflict Archive on the Internet]] (CAIN).</ref> Devenny suffered a heart attack and died on 17 July from his injuries. |- |valign="top"| 13 July |During clashes with nationalists throwing stones at an Orange Hall in [[Dungiven]], RUC officers beat Francis McCloskey, a Catholic civilian (aged 67). He died of his injuries the next day. Many consider this the first death of the Troubles.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1969] ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 August |The UVF planted their first bomb in the [[Republic of Ireland]], damaging the [[RTÉ Television Centre]] in Dublin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bomb damages RTÉ studios|url=http://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/681-history-of-rte/704-rte-1960s/139354-bomb-damages-rte-tv-studios|publisher=RTÉ.ie|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 12–14 August |[[Battle of the Bogside]] – during an [[Apprentice Boys of Derry|Apprentice Boys]] march, serious rioting erupted in Derry between Irish nationalists and the RUC. RUC officers, backed by loyalists, entered the nationalist Bogside in armoured cars and tried to suppress the riot by using [[CS gas]], [[water cannon]] and eventually firearms. The almost continuous rioting lasted for two days.<ref name="ReferenceA">[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1969] ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 10 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 14–17 August |[[Northern Ireland riots of August 1969]] – in response to events in Derry, Irish nationalists held protests throughout Northern Ireland. Some of these became violent. In Belfast, loyalists responded by attacking nationalist districts. Rioting also erupted in [[Newry]], [[Armagh]], [[Crossmaglen]], [[Dungannon]], [[Coalisland]] and [[Dungiven]]. Six Catholics and two Protestants were shot dead and at least 133 were treated for gunshot wounds. Scores of houses and businesses were burnt out, most of them owned by Catholics. Thousands of families, mostly Catholics, were forced to flee their homes and [[refugee camp]]s were set up in the Republic.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> The [[British Army]] was deployed on the streets of Northern Ireland, which marked the beginning of [[Operation Banner]]. |- |valign="top"| 11 October |Three people were shot dead during street violence in the loyalist Shankill area of Belfast. Two were Protestant civilians (George Dickie and Herbert Hawe) shot by the British Army and one was an RUC officer (Victor Arbuckle) shot by the UVF. Arbuckle was the first RUC officer to be killed in the Troubles. The loyalists "had taken to the streets in protest at the Hunt Report, which recommended the disbandment of the [[Ulster Special Constabulary|B Specials]] and disarming of the RUC".<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch69.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1969] ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 10 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| October–December |The UVF detonated bombs in the Republic of Ireland. In Dublin it detonated a [[car bomb]] near the [[Garda Síochána]] central detective bureau.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VQMgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TGQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6100%2C7970659 "Irish tighten security after Dublin bombing"], ''The Lewiston Daily Sun'', 29 December 1969.</ref> It also bombed a power station at [[Ballyshannon]], a [[Wolfe Tone]] memorial in [[Bodenstown]], and the [[Daniel O'Connell]] monument in Dublin.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| December |A split formed in the Irish Republican Army, creating what was to become the [[Official IRA]] and [[Provisional IRA]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
==1970–1979== ===1970=== {|"floatright" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 31 March |Following an [[Orange Order]] march, intense riots erupted on the [[Springfield Road, Belfast|Springfield Road]] in Belfast. Violence lasted for three days, and the British Army used [[CS gas]] for the first time in large quantities. About 38 soldiers and dozens of civilians were injured.<ref name=cainchron70>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch70.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – 1970], ''CAIN Web Service''.</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 3 April |[[Ian Freeland]]—the British Army's [[General officer commanding|overall commander]] in Northern Ireland—announced that anyone throwing [[Molotov cocktail|petrol bombs]] would be shot dead if they did not heed a warning from soldiers.<ref name=cainchron70/> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"|19 June |[[Edward Heath]] became [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] after winning a majority in the general election. |- |valign="top"| 27–28 June |Following the arrest of [[Bernadette Devlin]], intense riots erupted in parts of Derry and Belfast. Further violence erupted in Belfast following Orange marches past Catholic neighbourhoods. This led to [[Battle of Saint Matthew's|gun battles between republicans and loyalists]]. Seven people were killed. |- |valign="top"| 3–5 July |[[Falls Curfew]] – a British Army raid in the [[Falls Road, Belfast|Falls]] district of Belfast developed into a riot between soldiers and residents and then gun battles between soldiers and the 'Official' IRA. The British Army sealed off the area, imposed a 36-hour curfew and raided hundreds of homes under the cover of CS gas. Three Catholic civilians (Charles O'Neill, William Burns and Patrick Elliman) as well as a British journalist of Polish descent, Zbigniew Uglik, were killed by the British Army, sixty others were injured, and 300 were arrested. Fifteen soldiers were shot by the OIRA. |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 2 August |[[Rubber bullets]] were used for the first time.<ref>The Times, 3 August 1970, ''Ulster offers £50,000 to stop bombs''.</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| August |The constitutional nationalist [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP) was formed. |}
===1971=== {|"floatright" style="background:#ffd;" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 3–6 February |Under pressure from the [[Chichester-Clark ministry|unionist government of Northern Ireland]], the British Army began a series of raids in nationalist areas of Belfast, sparking three days of violence.<ref>Reed, David. ''Ireland: The Key to the British Revolution''. Larkin Publications, 1984. pp. 158-59</ref> On 6 February, British soldiers shot dead Catholic civilian Bernard Watt in [[Ardoyne]] and IRA member James Saunders in Oldpark, claiming both were armed.<ref>McKittrick, David. ''Lost Lives''. Mainstream, 2001. p. 63</ref> Shortly after, the IRA shot dead British soldier [[Robert Curtis (soldier)|Robert Curtis]] during rioting in [[New Lodge, Belfast|New Lodge]]. He was the first on-duty British soldier killed in the Troubles.<ref>White, Robert William (1993). ''Provisional Irish republicans: an oral and interpretive history'', p. 81, Greenwood Publishing Group; {{ISBN|978-0-313-28564-6}}.</ref> The next day, [[James Chichester-Clark]], [[Prime Minister of Northern Ireland]], declared that "Northern Ireland is at war with the Irish Republican Army Provisionals".<ref>McKittrick, p. 65</ref> |- |valign="top"| 9 March |[[Three Scottish soldiers killings|Three off-duty Scottish soldiers]] (John McCaig, Joseph McCaig and Dougald McCaughey) were shot dead by the IRA after being lured from a pub in Belfast. Two days later, 4,000 loyalist shipyard workers took to the streets to demand the mass [[internment]] of Irish republicans. |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 23 March |[[Brian Faulkner]] became the Prime Minister of Northern Ireland. |- |valign="top"| 25 May |The IRA threw a time bomb into Springfield Road British Army/RUC base in Belfast, killing British Army Sergeant [[Michael Willetts]] and wounding seven RUC officers, two British soldiers and eighteen civilians. |- |valign="top"| 8 July |During street disturbances, British soldiers shot dead two Catholic civilians (Desmond Beattie and Seamus Cusack) in [[Free Derry]]. As a result, riots erupted in the city and the SDLP withdrew from Stormont in protest.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch71.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1971], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| August |[[Operation Demetrius]]: [[internment]] was introduced. Armed soldiers launched [[police raid|dawn raids]] throughout Northern Ireland, arresting 342 people suspected of being involved with the IRA. Most of those arrested were Catholics who had no links with republican paramilitaries, and many reported that they and their families were beaten and threatened by soldiers. This sparked four days of violence in which 20 civilians, two IRA members (Patrick McAdorey and Seamus Simpson) and two British soldiers were killed. Fourteen of the civilians, including a Catholic priest, Father Hugh Mullan, were killed by British soldiers; 11 of them in the [[Ballymurphy massacre]]. Winston Donnell (22) became the first [[Ulster Defence Regiment]] (UDR) soldier to die in 'the Troubles' when he was shot by the IRA near [[Clady, County Tyrone]]. An estimated 7,000 people, mostly Catholics, were forced to flee their homes. The introduction of internment caused a major, long-term increase in violence.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch71.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1971], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| September |Loyalists formed the [[Ulster Defence Association]] (UDA). The group would quickly become the largest loyalist group in Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch71.htm#Sep A Chronology of the Conflict – September 1971], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 2 November |[[Red Lion Pub bombing]] - the Provisional IRA exploded a bomb inside a pub on the [[Shankill Road]], Belfast. The blast killed three Protestant civilians and around 30 other people were injured, some seriously. There was also a bombing in drapery shop at the same time right beside the pub which injured several more people. |- |valign="top"| 4 December |[[McGurk's Bar bombing]] – the UVF exploded a bomb at a Catholic-owned pub in Belfast, killing fifteen Catholic civilians (including two children) and wounding seventeen others. This was the highest death toll from a single incident in Belfast during the Troubles.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 11 December |[[1971 Balmoral Furniture Company bombing|Balmoral Showroom bombing]] – a bomb exploded outside a furniture showroom on the mainly-Protestant and loyalist [[Shankill Road]], Belfast. Four civilians, two adults (Hugh Bruce, a Protestant, and Harold King, a Catholic), and two babies, Tracey Munn (2 years old) and Colin Nichol (17 months old) were killed. The babies both died instantly when part of the wall crashed down upon the pram they were sharing. The adult employees were killed and nineteen people were wounded. The IRA was blamed.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
===1972=== ===January–June=== {|"floatright" |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 30 January |[[Bloody Sunday (1972)|Bloody Sunday]] – 26 unarmed civilians were shot (of whom 13 were killed and one fatally wounded) by the British Army during a massive anti-internment demonstration in Derry. One of the dead, [[Gerard Donaghy]], was a member of [[Fianna Éireann]] and reportedly had nail bombs on his person. After a lengthy examination of the evidence in the Inquiry's Report, Lord Saville concluded that "in our view Gerald Donaghey (sic) was probably in possession of the nail bombs when he was shot", but noted "... for reasons given elsewhere in this report ... Donaghey (sic) was not shot because of his possession of nail bombs".<ref>[http://report.bloody-sunday-inquiry.org/volume07/chapter145/#the-report Bloody Sunday Inquiry] - volume 07, chapter 145 {{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>
This was the highest death toll from a single shooting incident during the Troubles. |- |valign="top"| 2 February |Funerals of eleven of those killed on Bloody Sunday. Prayer services held across Ireland. In Dublin, over 30,000 marched to the British Embassy, carrying thirteen replica coffins and black flags. They attacked the Embassy with stones and bottles, then petrol bombs. The building was eventually burnt to the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jAuiFeVpUSs |title=British Embassy attacked in Dublin |publisher=YouTube |date=2006-02-25 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 February |[[1972 Aldershot Bombing|Aldershot bombing]] – seven people were killed by an Official IRA car bomb at Aldershot Barracks in England. It was thought to be in retaliation for Bloody Sunday. Six of those killed were ancillary workers (five female and one male), and the seventh was a Roman Catholic British Army chaplain (Father Gerry Weston, aka Captain Gerard Weston, MBE), who had recently returned from service in Northern Ireland. The six others were Thelma Bosley, Margaret Grant, John Haslar, Joan Lunn, Jill Mansfield, and Cherie Munton.<ref>{{cite news|last=Woollacott|first=Martin|title=From the archives: IRA kills 7 in raid on Paras' English base|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2009/feb/23/ira-bomb-paras-aldershot-1972|newspaper=The Guardian|date=23 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/february/22/newsid_2519000/2519029.stm|title=1972: IRA bomb kills six at Aldershot barracks|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 4 March |[[Abercorn Restaurant bombing]] – a bomb exploded in a crowded restaurant in Belfast, killing two Catholic civilians (Anne Owens and Janet Bereen) and wounding 130. Many were badly maimed. The IRA was blamed. |- |valign="top"| 20 March |[[1972 Donegall Street bombing]] – the PIRA detonated its first car bomb, on Donegall Street in Belfast. Allegedly due to inadequate warnings, four civilians (Sydney Bell, Ernest Dougan, James Macklin, and Henry Miller), two RUC officers (Ernest McAllister and Bernard O'Neill) and a UDR soldier (Samuel Trainor) were killed while 148 people were wounded. |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 30 March |Northern Ireland's Government and Parliament were dissolved by the British Government. [[Direct rule over Northern Ireland|Direct rule]] from [[Her Majesty's Government|Westminster]] was introduced. |- |valign="top"| 14 April |The PIRA exploded twenty-four bombs in towns and cities across Northern Ireland. There were fourteen shootouts between the PIRA and security forces.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch72.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1972], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 April |An 11-year-old boy (Francis Rowntree) was killed by a rubber bullet fired by the British Army in Belfast. He was the first person to die from a rubber bullet impact. |- |valign="top"| 13–14 May |[[Battle at Springmartin]] – following a loyalist car bombing of a Catholic-owned pub in the [[Ballymurphy, Belfast|Ballymurphy]] area of Belfast, clashes erupted between the PIRA, UVF and British Army. Seven people were killed: five civilians (four Catholics, one Protestant), a British soldier, and a member of the [[Fianna Éireann]] (PIRA youth wing). |- |valign="top"| 28 May |Four PIRA [[Volunteer (Irish republican)|volunteer]]s and four civilians were killed when a bomb they were preparing exploded prematurely at a house on Anderson Street, Belfast. |- style="background:#ffd;" |valign="top"| 29 May |The [[Official Irish Republican Army|Official IRA]] announced a ceasefire. This marked the end of the Official IRA's military campaign. |}
===July–December=== {|"floatright" |- |valign="top"| 9 July |[[Springhill Massacre]] – British snipers shot dead five Catholics (2 civilians, 2 members of [[Fianna Éireann]], and a Roman Catholic priest) and wounded two others in Springhill, Belfast.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 13 July |There was a series of gun-battles and shootings across Belfast. The PIRA shot dead three British Army soldiers (David Meeke, Kenneth Mogg, and Martin Rooney), and the British Army shot dead two civilians (Thomas Burns and Terence Toolan)and a PIRA volunteer (James Reid).{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 14 July |There was a series of gun-battles and shootings across Belfast. The PIRA shot dead three British Army soldiers (Peter Heppenstall, John Williams and Robert Williams-Wynn). The British Army shot dead a PIRA volunteer (Louis Scullion) and an OIRA volunteer (Edward Brady), while a Protestant civilian (Jane McIntyre) was shot dead in crossfire.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 21 July |[[Bloody Friday (1972)|Bloody Friday]] – within the space of 75 minutes, the PIRA exploded twenty-two bombs in Belfast, killing nine people: five civilians (William Crothers, Jackie Gibson, Thomas Killops, Brigid Murray, Margaret O'Hare and Stephen Parker), two British Army soldiers (Stephen Cooper and Philip Price) and one UDA [[volunteer (Ulster loyalist)|volunteer]] (William Irvine) were killed, while 130 were injured. |- |valign="top"| 31 July |[[Operation Motorman]] – the British Army used 12,000 soldiers supported by tanks and bulldozers to re-take the "no-go areas" controlled by the PIRA. |- |valign="top"| 31 July |[[Claudy bombing]] – nine civilians (five Catholics and four Protestants) were killed when three car bombs exploded in [[Claudy]], County Londonderry. No group has since claimed responsibility but the late Father James Chesney, a local Catholic priest, who was the IRA's quartermaster and Director of Operations of the [[South Derry Brigade]], was later implicated (see,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inishowennews.com/06JamesChesney0629.htm |title=Fr James Chesney was moved to Malin Head after Claudy bombing |publisher=Inishowennews.com |date=1972-07-31 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-11058002 |title=Who was Father James Chesney? - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.com |date=2010-08-24 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Owen Bowcott |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/aug/24/claudy-bombing-profile-father-chesney |title=Claudy bombings: Father Chesney, the 'Provo Priest' &#124; UK news |publisher=The Guardian |date=2010-08-24 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref>, <ref>[http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/claudy-terror-suspect-priest-chesney-met-sinn-feins-martin-mcguinness-28557715.html]{{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref>). |- |valign="top"| 20 Dec. |Five civilians, four Catholics (Bernard Kelly, Charles McCafferty, Francis McCarron, and Michael McGinley) and one Protestant (Charles Moore), were killed in gun attack on the Top of the Hill Bar, Strabane Old Road, [[Waterside, Derry]].<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=20&month=12&year=1972 Sutton Index of Deaths – 20 December 1972], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> It is believed the UDA was responsible.<ref>McKittrick, David. ''Lost Lives''. Mainstream, 1999. p. 309</ref> |}
===1973=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 4 February |British Army snipers shot dead a PIRA volunteer and three civilians at the junction of Edlingham Street and New Lodge Road, Belfast.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron/1973.html Sutton Index of Deaths – 1973], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- | valign="top"| 7 February |The United Loyalist Council held a one-day strike to "re-establish some sort of Protestant or loyalist control over the affairs of the province". Loyalist paramilitaries forcibly tried to stop many people going to work and to close any businesses that had opened. There were eight bombings and thirty-five arsons. Three loyalist paramilitaries and one civilian were killed.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- | valign="top"| 8 March |[[1973 Old Bailey Bombing]] – The PIRA undertook its first operation in England, when it planted four car bombs in London. Ten members of the PIRA team, including [[Gerry Kelly]] and the Price sisters, were arrested at [[Heathrow Airport]] while trying to leave the country. |- | valign="top"| 17 May |Five British Army soldiers (Barry Cox, Frederick Drake, Arthur Place, Derek Reed, and Sheridan Young) were killed by a PIRA booby-trap bomb outside Knock-na-Moe Castle Hotel, Omagh, County Tyrone.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch73.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1973], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 12 June |[[1973 Coleraine bombings]] – six Protestant pensioners (Dinah Campbell, Francis Campbell, Elizabeth Craigmile, Nan Davis, Elizabeth Palmer and Robert Scott) were killed and 33 other people wounded by a PIRA car bomb on Railway Road, [[Coleraine]], County Londonderry. The warning given before the explosion had been inadequate.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch73.htm#Jun A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1973], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 28 June |[[Northern Ireland Assembly]] elections took place. |- |valign="top"| 31 October |[[1973 Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape|Mountjoy Prison escape]] – three PIRA volunteers escaped from Mountjoy Prison in [[Dublin]] using a hijacked helicopter. |- |valign="top"| December |The [[Sunningdale Agreement]] was signed. |}
===1974=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 4 February |[[M62 coach bombing]] – eight British Army soldiers and three civilians (the wife and two children of one of the soldiers who was killed) are killed when a PIRA bomb exploded on a bus as it was travelling along the [[M62 motorway]] in [[West Yorkshire]], England. |- |valign="top"| 4 March |[[Harold Wilson]] defeats [[Edward Heath]] in the general election to become British Prime Minister, it is his second time in office, the first being from 1964-1970. |- |valign="top"| 20 April |The Troubles claimed its 1000th victim, James Murphy, a petrol station owner in [[County Fermanagh]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/april/20/newsid_2525000/2525369.stm 'Troubles' death toll hits 1,000], ''BBC On This Day'', 20 April 1974</ref> |- |valign="top"| 2 May |Six Catholic civilians (Francis Brennan, James Doherty, Thomas Ferguson, John Gallagher, William Kelly and Thomas Morrissey) were killed and eighteen wounded when the UVF exploded a bomb at Rose & Crown Bar on Ormeau Road, Belfast.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch74.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1974], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"| 15 May |Beginning of the [[Ulster Workers' Council strike]]. |- |valign="top"| 17 May |[[Dublin and Monaghan bombings]] – the UVF exploded four bombs (three in Dublin, one in Monaghan) in the [[Republic of Ireland]]. They killed thirty-three civilians and wounded a further 300. This was the highest number of casualties in a single incident during "The Troubles". It has been alleged that members of the British security forces were involved. The UVF did not claim responsibility until 15 July 1993.<ref>[http://www.triskelle.eu/history/directrule.php?index=060.170.050 Direct Rule], Triskelle.eu; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 28 May |The [[Northern Ireland Executive]] collapsed. As a result, direct rule was re-introduced.<ref>[http://encyclopedia.farlex.com/1974 1974], Farlex</ref> |- |valign="top"| 17 June |The Provisional IRA bombed the [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]] in London, injuring 11 people and causing extensive damage.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/june/17/newsid_2514000/2514827.stm IRA bombs parliament], ''BBC On This Day'', 17 June 1974</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 October |[[Guildford pub bombings]] – four British soldiers (William Forsyth, Ann Hamilton, John Hunter and Caroline Slater) and one civilian (Paul Craig) were killed by PIRA bombs at two pubs in [[Guildford]], England. |- |valign="top"| 7 November |[[Kings Arms, Woolwich|1974 Woolwich bombing]] - two people (a British soldier and a civilian) were killed and 28 injured when the IRA threw a 6 lb gelignite bomb with the addition of shrapnel through the window of the Kings Arms pub in [[Woolwich]], England . |- |valign="top"| 21 November |[[Birmingham pub bombings]] – twenty-one civilians were killed when bombs exploded at two pubs in [[Birmingham]], England. This was the deadliest attack in England during the Troubles. The "[[Birmingham Six]]" would be tried for this and convicted. Many years later, after new evidence of police fabrication and suppression of evidence, their convictions would be quashed and they would be released. |- |valign="top"| 10 December |The [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA) and its political wing the [[Irish Republican Socialist Party]] (IRSP) was founded at the Spa Hotel in the village of [[Lucan]] near [[Dublin]]. |- |valign="top"| 22 December |The PIRA announced a [[Christmas]] ceasefire.<ref>White, R. W. (1993). ''Provisional Irish republicans: an oral and interpretive history.'' Greenwood Publishing Group. p. 136.</ref> Before the ceasefire, they carried out a bomb attack on the home of former Prime Minister [[Edward Heath]]. Heath was not in the building at the time and no one was injured.<ref name=mul>[http://www.museumoflondon.org.uk/English/Collections/OnlineResources/X20L/Themes/1380/1150/ IRA Bomb Campaigns], museumoflondon.org.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1975=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 10 February |The PIRA agreed to a truce and ceasefire with the British government and the Northern Ireland Office. Seven "incident centres" were established in nationalist areas to monitor the ceasefire and the response of the security forces.<ref name="cain.ulst.ac.uk">[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Feb A Chronology of the Conflict – February 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 20 February |A feud began between the Official IRA (OIRA) and the Irish National Liberation Army (INLA). The two groups assassinated a number of each other's volunteers until the feud ended in June 1975.<ref name="cain.ulst.ac.uk"/> |- |valign="top"| March |A feud began between the Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF) and Ulster Defence Association (UDA), resulting in a number of assassinations.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Mar A Chronology of the Conflict – March 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- 140375. |- |valign="top"| 13 March |A unit from the UVF's Belfast Brigade attempted to bomb the Catholic owned Peter Conway's bar on the Shore Road in Greencastle, Belfast. The bomb exploded prematurely, killing a Catholic civilian woman and one of the UVF bombers. <ref>http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=13&month=03&year=1975</ref> |- |valign="top"| 6 April |Daniel Loughran (18), then a member of the People's Liberation Army (PLA), which later became the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA), was shot dead at [[Divis Tower|Divis Flats]], Belfast, by members of the Official Irish Republican Army (OIRA) in the continuing feud between the OIRA and the INLA.<ref name="CAIN Web Service 2015">[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 12 April |Five Catholic civilians (Marie Bennett, Elizabeth Carson, Mary McAleavey, Agnes McAnoy, and Arthur Penn) were killed in a UVF gun and grenade attack on the Strand Bar, Anderson Street, Short Strand, Belfast. Another Catholic civilian (Michael Mulligan) died of his injuries on 20 April 1975. Elizabeth Carson's husband, Willy, lost an arm in the attack. <ref name="CAIN Web Service 2015"/><br>Paul Crawford (25), then a member of the Official Irish Republican Army (OIRA), was shot dead on the Falls Road, Belfast. This killing was another in the feud between the OIRA and the Irish National Liberation Army (INLA).<ref name="CAIN Web Service 2015"/> |- |valign="top"| 22 June |The UVF tried to derail a train by planting a bomb on the railway line near [[Straffan]], [[County Kildare]], Republic of Ireland. A civilian, Christopher Phelan, tried to stop the UVF members, and was stabbed-to-death. His actions, however, reportedly delayed the explosion long enough to allow the train to pass safely.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 17 July |Four British soldiers (Calvert Brown, Edward Garside, Robert McCarter, and Peter Willis) were killed by a PIRA remote-controlled bomb near [[Forkill]], County Armagh. The attack was the first major breach of the February truce.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 31 July |[[Miami Showband massacre]] – UVF members (some of whom were also UDR soldiers) shot dead three musicians (Tony Geraghty and Fran O'Toole, both from the Republic of Ireland, and Brian McCoy, a Northern Irish Protestant), members of the [[Irish showband]] called "Miami Showband", at Buskhill, County Down. The gunmen staged a bogus military checkpoint, stopped the showband's [[minibus]] and ordered the musicians out. Two UDR soldiers (Harris Boyle and Wesley Somerville) hid a [[time bomb]] in the bus, but it exploded prematurely and they were killed. The other gunmen then opened fire on the musicians and fled. Three UDR soldiers were later convicted for their part in the attack, which has been linked to the "[[Glenanne gang]]".{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 13 August |[[Bayardo Bar attack]] – PIRA volunteers carried out a gun and bomb attack on the Bayardo Bar, a pub in Belfast frequented by UVF commanders. Four Protestant civilians (Linda Boyle, William Gracey, Samuel Gunning, and Joanne McDowell), and one UVF member (Hugh Harris) were killed. |- |valign="top"| 27 August |[[Caterham Arms pub bombing]] - The Provisional IRA exploded a bomb in a [[Caterham]] pub injuring 33 people (10 soldiers & 23 civilians). This marked the end of their ceasefire in England. |- |valign="top"| 1 September |Five Protestant civilians (William Herron, John Johnston, Nevin McConnell, James McKee, and Ronald McKee) were killed and seven were wounded in a gun attack on Tullyvallen [[Orange Order|Orange Hall]] near [[Newtownhamilton]], County Armagh.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Sep A Chronology of the Conflict – September 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> One of the Orangemen was an off-duty RUC officer, who returned fire.<ref>McKittrick, David. ''Lost Lives''. Mainstream Publishing, 1999. p. 572</ref> The attack was claimed by the [[South Armagh Republican Action Force]] (SARAF), which claimed it was retaliation for "the assassinations of fellow Catholics in Belfast".<ref>English, Richard. ''Armed Struggle: The history of the IRA''. Pan McMillen, 2004. p. 171<!-- ISBN needed --></ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 September |[[London Hilton bombing]] - The Provisional IRA exploded a bomb in the lobby of the Hilton hotel in London killing two people and injuring 63 |- |valign="top"| 2 October |The UVF killed seven civilians in a series of attacks across Northern Ireland. Six were Catholics (Frances Donnelly, Gerard Grogan, Marie McGrattan, Thomas Murphy, Thomas Osbourne, and John Stewart) and one was a Protestant (Irene Nicholson). Four UVF members (Mark Dodd, Robert Freeman, Aubrey Reid, Samuel Swanson) were killed when the bomb they were transporting prematurely exploded as they drove along a road in Farrenlester, County Londonderry, near [[Coleraine]].<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 9 October |[[Green Park Tube Station Bombing]] - One person was killed and 20 injured when the IRA exploded a bomb in Green Park, near [[Piccadilly]], London |- |valign="top"| 12 November |[[Scott's Oyster Bar bombing]] - One person was killed and 15 injured when the IRA threw a bomb through a restaurant in London's West End. |- |valign="top"| 18 November |[[Walton's Restaurant bombing]] - Two civilians were killed and 23 civilians injured when the Provisional IRA threw a bomb without warning into a restaurant in [[Walton Street]], [[Chelsea, London]]. The IRA unit who carried out this attack was also responsible for the Caterham, Hilton Hotel, Green Park and Scott's Oyster bombings in recent weeks. See: [[Provisional IRA's Balcombe Street Gang]] |- |valign="top"| 22 November |[[Drummuckavall Ambush]] – three British Army soldiers (James Duncan, Peter McDonald and Michael Sampson) were killed and one soldier was wounded when the PIRA attacked a watchtower in Drummuckavall, Crossmaglen, South Armagh. |- |valign="top"| 25 November |A loyalist gang nicknamed the "[[Shankill Butchers]]" undertook its first "cut-throat killing" (that of Francis Crossen). The gang was named for its late-night kidnapping, torture and murder (by throat slashing) of random Catholic civilians in Belfast. |- |valign="top"| 5 December |End of internment. |- |valign="top"| 6 December |[[Balcombe Street Siege]] – for six days, four PIRA volunteers held two hostages at an apartment in [[London]]. |- |valign="top"| 19 December |The [[Red Hand Commandos]] exploded a no-warning car bomb in [[Dundalk]], killing two civilians (Jack Rooney and Hugh Watters) and wounding twenty. Shortly after, the same group launched a gun and bomb attack across the border in [[Silverbridge, County Armagh|Silverbridge]]. Two local Catholic civilians and brothers (Michael and Patrick Donnelly) and an English civilian (Trevor Brecknell), married to a local woman, were killed in that attack, while six others were wounded. The attacks have been linked to the "[[Glenanne gang]]".<ref>Cassell Report (2006), p. 51</ref><ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Dec A Chronology of the Conflict – December 1975], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |}
===1976=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 4–5 January |[[Reavey and O'Dowd killings]] – the UVF shot dead six Catholic civilians from two families (one group was a trio of brothers; the other was an uncle and two nephews) in co-ordinated attacks in County Armagh. An officer in the RUC [[Special Patrol Group (RUC)|Special Patrol Group]] took part in the killings, which have been linked to the "[[Glenanne gang]]". [[Kingsmill massacre]] – in retaliation for [[Reavey and O'Dowd killings]], the South Armagh Republican Action Force shot eleven Protestant men after stopping their minibus at Kingsmill, County Armagh. Ten died; one survived despite being shot 18 times. |- |valign="top"| 23 January |The PIRA truce of February 1975 was officially brought to an end.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch76.htm#Jan A Chronology of the Conflict – January 1976], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| March |End of [[Special Category Status]] for prisoners convicted of terrorist crimes. |- |valign="top"| 16 March |[[Harold Wilson]] announced his resignation as British Prime Minister, taking effect on 5 April 1976. |- |valign="top"| 17 March |Four Catholic civilians, including two children (Patrick Barnard, Joseph Kelly, James McCaughey, and Andrew Small) were killed and twelve wounded when the UVF exploded a car bomb at Hillcrest Bar, [[Dungannon]]. The attack has been linked to the "[[Glenanne gang]]".<ref>[http://www.patfinucanecentre.org/sarmagh/collusion.pdf Cassel Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610155220/http://www.patfinucanecentre.org/sarmagh/collusion.pdf |date=10 June 2011 }} (2006), p. 53</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 April |[[James Callaghan]] was elected leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and succeeded [[Harold Wilson]] as Prime Minister of the United Kingdom. |- |valign="top"| 15 May |The UVF launched gun and bomb attacks on two pubs in [[Charlemont, County Armagh]], killing four Catholic civilians (Felix Clancy, Robert McCullough, Frederick McLoughlin, and Sean O'Hagan). A British Army UDR soldier was later convicted for taking part in the attacks.<ref>Cassell Report (2006), pp. 53-54</ref><br>The PIRA killed three RUC officers in County Fermanagh and one RUC officer in County Down.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch76.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1976], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 June |Nine civilians were killed during separate attacks in and around Belfast. After a suspected republican bombing killed two Protestant civilians (Robert Groves and Edward McMurray) in a pub, the UVF killed three Catholic civilians and two Protestant civilians, all males (Samuel Corr, James Coyle, Edward Farrell, John Martin, and Daniel McNeil) in a [[Chlorane Bar attack|gun and bomb attack at the Chlorane Bar]]. In a separate bomb attack on the International Bar, Portaferry, County Down, the UVF killed a Catholic civilian. The UDA/UFF also assassinated a member of Sinn Féin, Colm Mulgrew.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch76.htm#Jun A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1976], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref>
'''25 June 1976''' - Ruby Kidd (28), Francis Walker (17) and Joseph McBride (56), all Protestant civilians, were shot dead during an Republican Action Force gun attack on The Store Bar, Lyle Hill Road, [[Templepatrick]]. |- |valign="top"| 21 July |[[Ramble Inn attack]] – the UVF killed six civilians (five Protestants, one Catholic) in a gun attack at a pub near [[Antrim, County Antrim|Antrim]]. The pub was targeted because it was owned by Catholics. The victims were Frank Scott, Ernest Moore, James McCallion, Joseph Ellis, James Francey (all Protestants) and Oliver Woulahan, a Catholic.<ref name=July76>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch76.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1976], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 21 July |[[Christopher Ewart Biggs]] (the British Ambassador to Ireland) and his secretary, Judith Cook, were assassinated by a bomb planted in Mr Biggs' car in Dublin. Two others in the car were seriously injured.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} |- |valign="top"| 30 July |Four Protestant civilians were shot dead at a pub off Milltown Road, Belfast. The attack was claimed by the Republican Action Force.<ref name=July76/> |- |valign="top"| 10 August |A PIRA volunteer (Danny Lennon) was shot dead by the British Army as he drove along a road in Belfast. His car then went out of control and killed three children. This incident sparked a series of "peace rallies" throughout the month. The group that organised the rallies became known as Peace People, and was led by [[Mairead Corrigan]] and [[Betty Williams (Northern Ireland)|Betty Williams]]. Their rallies were the first (since the conflict began) where large numbers of Protestants and Catholics joined forces to campaign for peace.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch76.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1976], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 29 April 2017.</ref> |- |valign="top"| September |[[Blanket protest]]s began in the [[Maze prison]], in protest at the end of special category status. The term 'blanket protest' comes from the protesters refusal to wear prison uniforms, instead wrapping blankets around themselves.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} |}
===1977=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 11 December |[[Mairead Corrigan]] and [[Betty Williams (Northern Ireland)|Betty Williams]] received the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].<ref>[http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/1976 The Nobel Peace Prize, 1976], Nobelprize.org; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1978=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 17 February |[[La Mon restaurant bombing]] – eleven civilians and an RUC officer were killed and thirty wounded by a PIRA incendiary bomb at the La Mon Restaurant near Belfast. |- |valign="top"| 17 June |The PIRA killed an RUC officer (Hugh McConnell) and kidnapped and murdered another (William Turbitt), near [[Crossmaglen]], County Armagh. The following day, loyalist paramilitaries kidnapped a Catholic priest and vowed to hold him hostage until the RUC officer was freed. However, they released the priest shortly thereafter under pressure from the authorities and church leaders. In December 1978 the kidnappers were charged with the kidnapping and the murder of a Catholic shopkeeper, William Strathearn.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch78.htm#Jun A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1978], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 21 June |The British Army shot dead three PIRA volunteers (Denis Brown, William Mailey, and James Mulvenna) and a passing UVF member (William Hanna, in a case of mistaken identity) at a postal depot on Ballysillan Road, Belfast. It is claimed that the PIRA volunteers were about to launch a bomb attack.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron/1978.html Sutton Index of Deaths – 1978], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 21 September |The PIRA exploded bombs at the [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] airfield near [[Eglinton, County Londonderry]]. The terminal building, two aircraft hangars and four planes were destroyed.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch78.htm#Sep A Chronology of the Conflict – September 1978], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 14–19 November |The PIRA exploded over fifty bombs in towns across Northern Ireland, injuring thirty-seven people. Belfast, Derry, [[Armagh]], [[Castlederg]], [[Cookstown]] and [[Enniskillen]] were hardest hit.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch78.htm#Nov A Chronology of the Conflict – November 1978], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1979=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 20 February |Eleven loyalists known as the "[[Shankill Butchers]]" were sentenced to life in prison for nineteen murders. The gang was named for its late-night kidnapping, torture and murder (by throat slashing) of random Catholic civilians in Belfast.<!--the gang did kill some Protestants but none of them were mutilated--> |- |valign="top"|22 March |The PIRA assassinated [[Richard Sykes (diplomat)|Richard Sykes]], the British ambassador to the Netherlands, along with his valet, Karel Straub, in [[The Hague|Den Haag]]. The group also exploded twenty-four bombs in various locations across Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch79.htm#Mar A Chronology of the Conflict – March 1979], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"|30 March |The INLA assassinated [[Airey Neave]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] and advisor to [[Margaret Thatcher]]. The INLA exploded a booby-trap bomb underneath his car as he left the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], [[London]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"|17 April |Four RUC officers were killed by a PIRA van bomb in [[Bessbrook]], County Armagh. The bomb was estimated at 1000&nbsp;lb, believed to be the largest PIRA bomb used up to that point.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch79.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1979], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"|4 May |[[Margaret Thatcher]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] wins a landslide victory to become [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] defeating the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] who were in power for six years. |- |valign="top"|27 August |[[Warrenpoint ambush]] – eighteen British Army soldiers were killed when the PIRA exploded two roadside bombs as a British convoy passed [[Narrow Water Castle]] near [[Warrenpoint]]. There was a brief exchange of fire, and the British Army shot dead a civilian. This was the British Army's highest death toll from a single attack during the Troubles. On the same day, four people (including [[Lord Louis Mountbatten|Lord Mountbatten]], a cousin of [[Queen Elizabeth II|the Queen]]) were killed by a PIRA bomb on board a boat near the coast of [[County Sligo]]. |- |valign="top"|September |During a visit to the Republic of Ireland, Pope [[John Paul II]] appealed for an end to the violence in Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch79.htm#Sep A Chronology of the Conflict – September 1979], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"|16 December |Four British Army soldiers (Allan Ayrton, William Beck, Simon Evans, and Keith Richards) were killed by a PIRA landmine near [[Dungannon]], County Tyrone. Another British Army soldier (Peter Grundy) was killed by a PIRA landmine near Forkill, County Armagh, and an ex-UDR soldier (James Fowler) was shot dead in Omagh.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch79.htm#Dec A Chronology of the Conflict – December 1979], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
==1980–1989== ===1980=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 17 January |[[Dunmurry train explosion]] – a PIRA bomb prematurely detonated on a passenger train near Belfast, killing two civilians (Mark Cochrane and Max Olorunda) as well as one of the bombers (Kevin Delaney), and severely injuring five (including the other bomber, Patrick Flynn). |- |valign="top"| 10 June |Eight PIRA prisoners escaped from [[Crumlin Road Gaol]] in Belfast. Using handguns that had been smuggled into the prison, they took prison officers hostage and shot their way out of the building.<ref name="c81"/> |- |valign="top"| October |Republican prisoners in the Maze began a [[hunger strike]] in protest against the end of [[special category status]]. |- |valign="top"| December |First Republican hunger strike called off. |}
===1981=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 21 January |[[Norman Stronge|Sir Norman Stronge]] and his son [[James Stronge (Mid-Armagh MP)|James Stronge]] (both former UUP MPs) were assassinated by the IRA at their home [[Tynan Abbey]], which was then burnt down. |- |valign="top"| 1 March |Republican prisoners in the Maze began a [[1981 Irish hunger strike|second hunger strike]]. |- |valign="top"| 9 April |Hunger striker [[Bobby Sands]] won a by-election to be elected as a [[Member of Parliament]] at Westminster. The law was later changed to prevent prisoners standing in elections. |- |valign="top"| 5 May |After 66 days on hunger strike, Sands died in the Maze. Nine further hunger strikers died in the following 3 months. |- |valign="top"| 19 May |Five British Army soldiers (Michael Bagshaw, Paul Bulman, Andrew Gavin, John King, and Grenville Winstone) were killed when their [[Alvis Saracen|Saracen APC]] was ripped apart by a PIRA roadside bomb at Chancellor's Road, Altnaveigh, near [[Bessbrook]], County Armagh.<ref name=c81>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron/1981.html|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,954798,00.html Northern Ireland: Death Cycle Monday, 1 June 1981], time.com; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 17 July |[[Glasdrumman ambush]] – the PIRA attacked a British Army post in South Armagh, killing one soldier (Lance Corporal Gavin Dean) and injuring another (Rifleman John Moore). |- |valign="top"| 1 September |Northern Ireland's first religiously integrated secondary school opened. |- |valign="top"| 3 October |Republican hunger strike ended. |}
===1982=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 20 April |The PIRA exploded bombs in Belfast, Derry, [[Armagh]], [[Ballymena]], [[Bessbrook]] and [[Magherafelt]]. Two civilians were killed and twelve were injured.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch82.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1982], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 17 August 2016.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 20 July |[[Hyde Park and Regent's Park bombings]] – eleven British soldiers and seven military horses died in PIRA bomb attacks during military ceremonies in Regent's Park and Hyde Park, London. Many spectators were badly injured. |- |valign="top"| 6 December |[[Droppin Well bombing]] – eleven British soldiers and six civilians were killed by an INLA time bomb at the Droppin' Well Bar in [[Ballykelly, County Londonderry|Ballykelly]], County Londonderry. |}
===1983=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 11 April |In the first 'supergrass' trial, fourteen UVF members were jailed for a total of two hundred years.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch83.htm#Apr A Chronology of the Conflict – April 1983], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 27 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| May |[[New Ireland Forum]] set up. |- |valign="top"| 13 July |Four British Army ([[Ulster Defence Regiment]]) soldiers (Ronald Alexander, Thomas Harron, John Roxborough, and Oswald Neely), all Protestant members of the 6th Battalion Ulster Defence Regiment, were killed when their vehicle struck a PIRA landmine near [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone|Ballygawley]], County Tyrone.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch83.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1983], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 27 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 August |In another 'supergrass' trial, twenty-two PIRA volunteers were jailed for a total of over four thousand years. Eighteen would later have their convictions quashed.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch83.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1983], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 27 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 25 September |[[Maze Prison escape]] – thirty-eight republican prisoners staged an elaborate escape from the [[Maze (HM Prison)|Maze Prison]] in County Antrim. One prison officer died of a heart attack after being stabbed by an escapee, and twenty others were injured, including two shot with guns that had been smuggled into the prison. Half of the escapees were recaptured within two days. Another drowned in [[County Fermanagh]] while trying to evade the police after the escape. Others were later captured but some evaded capture in the Republic of Ireland or the United States. |- |valign="top"| 17 December |[[Harrods bombing]] – a PIRA car bomb outside a department store in London killed six people, three civilians (Philip Geddes, Jasmine Cochrane-Patrick, and Kenneth Salvesen, a United States citizen), and three police officers, Sergeant Noel Lane, Constable Jane Arbuthnot and Inspector Stephen Dodd. Another policeman lost both legs and 90 people were injured. The PIRA's Army Council claimed it had not authorised the attack.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} |}
===1984=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 21 February |Two PIRA volunteers (Henry Hogan and Declan Martin) and a British soldier (Paul Oram) were killed during a shootout in [[Dunloy]], near [[Ballymoney]], County Antrim.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch84.htm#Feb A Chronology of the Conflict – February 1984], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 18 May |Three British soldiers (Thomas Agar, Robert Huggins, and Peter Gallimore) were killed by a PIRA landmine in [[Enniskillen]], County Fermanagh. Two RUC officers were killed by a PIRA landmine near [[Camlough]], South Armagh on the same day.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch84.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1984], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 12 October |[[Brighton hotel bombing]] – the PIRA carried out a bomb attack on the Grand Hotel, [[Brighton]], which was being used as a base for the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] Conference. Five people, including Sir [[Anthony Berry]], a Member of Parliament, died in the bombing, and others were maimed or injured. Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]] escaped harm. |- |valign="top"| December |Ian Thain became the first British soldier to be convicted of murdering a civilian during the Troubles.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch84.htm#Dec A Chronology of the Conflict – December 1984], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 2 December |One British soldier and two PIRA volunteers are killed in a [[Kesh ambush|SAS ambush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=2&month=12&year=1984 |title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths |publisher=Cain.ulst.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> | |}
===1985=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 28 February |[[1985 Newry mortar attack|Newry mortar attack]] – a PIRA mortar attack on an RUC base in [[Newry]] killed nine officers and wounded thirty-seven. This was the RUC's highest death toll from a single attack during the Troubles. |- |valign="top"| 20 May |Four RUC officers (David Baird, Tracy Doak, Stephen Rodgers, William Wilson) were killed on mobile patrol by a PIRA remote-controlled bomb near Killeen, County Armagh.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch85.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1985], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 15 November |Margaret Thatcher and [[Garret FitzGerald]] signed the [[Anglo-Irish Agreement]]. |- |valign="top"| December |All fifteen Unionist MPs at Westminster resigned in protest against the Anglo-Irish agreement. |- |valign="top"| 7 December |[[Attack on Ballygawley barracks]] – the PIRA launched an assault on the RUC barracks in [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone|Ballygawley]], County Tyrone. Two RUC officers (Constable George Gilliland and Reserve Constable William Clements) were killed. The barracks was completely destroyed by the subsequent bomb explosion and three other RUC officers were injured.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
===1986=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| June |[[Northern Ireland Assembly (1982)|Northern Ireland Assembly]]<ref>The previous link, [[Northern Ireland Assembly]], linked to the article on the current Northern Ireland Assembly, established in 1998. The Northern Ireland Assembly that was disbanded in 1986 was the one formed in 1982.</ref> was officially dissolved. |- |valign="top"| August |The PIRA issued a warning that anyone working with the security forces in Northern Ireland would be considered "part of the war machine" and would be "treated as collaborators".<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch86.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1986], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 2 November |During the [[Sinn Féin]] Ard Fheis (party conference) in Dublin, a majority of delegates voted to end the party's policy of [[abstentionism]] – refusing to take seats in [[Dáil Éireann]] (Irish parliament). This led to a split and [[Ruairí Ó Brádaigh]], [[Dáithí Ó Conaill]] and approximately 100 people staged a walk-out. The two men would form a new party called [[Republican Sinn Féin]].<ref name=Nov86>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch86.htm#Nov A Chronology of the Conflict – November 1986], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"| 10 November |Loyalists held a closed meeting at the Ulster Hall in Belfast. The main speakers at the meeting were [[Ian Paisley]], [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]] and [[Ivan Foster]]. During the meeting a new organisation, [[Ulster Resistance]], was formed to "take direct action as and when required" to end the Anglo-Irish Agreement.<ref name=Nov86/> |}
===1987=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 8 May |[[Loughgall Ambush]] – eight PIRA volunteers and one civilian were killed by the [[Special Air Service]] (SAS) in [[Loughall]], County Armagh. The eight-strong PIRA unit had just exploded a bomb at the RUC base when it was ambushed by the 24-strong SAS unit.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch87.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1987], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> |- |valign="top"| 8 November |[[Remembrance Day bombing]] – eleven civilians and an RUC officer were killed and sixty-three others were wounded by a PIRA bomb during a Remembrance Day service in [[Enniskillen]], County Fermanagh. One of those killed was Marie Wilson. In an emotional BBC interview, her father [[Gordon Wilson (peace campaigner)|Gordon Wilson]] (who was injured in the attack) expressed forgiveness towards his daughter's killer, and asked Loyalists not to seek revenge. He became a leading peace campaigner and was later elected to the Irish Senate. He died in 1995. |}
===1988=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| January |SDLP leader [[John Hume]] and Sinn Féin leader [[Gerry Adams]] held a meeting.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}{{When|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 6 March |[[Operation Flavius]] – three PIRA volunteers (Daniel McCann, Seán Savage and Mairéad Farrell) were killed by the [[Special Air Service|SAS]] in [[Gibraltar]]. |- |valign="top"| 16 March |[[Milltown Cemetery attack]] – at the funeral of those killed in Gibraltar, Loyalist [[Michael Stone (loyalist paramilitary)|Michael Stone]] (using pistols and grenades) attacked the mourners, killing one PIRA volunteer (Caoimhín Mac Brádaigh, a.k.a. Kevin Brady), and two civilians (Thomas McErlean and John Murray). More than 60 others were wounded. Much of the attack was filmed by television news crews. |- |valign="top"| 19 March |[[Corporals killings]] – at the funeral of Caoimhín Mac Brádaigh (aka Kevin Brady), who was killed in the Milltown Cemetery attack, two non-uniformed British Army corporals (David Howes and Derek Wood) were mistaken for loyalist gunmen and attacked by civilians after driving a car into the funeral procession. The two were later shot dead by the IRA.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 15 June |[[1988 Lisburn van bombing]] – six off-duty British Army soldiers (Signalman Mark Clavey, Lance Corporal Derek Green, Lance Corporal Graham Lambie, Corporal Ian Metcalf, Corporal William Patterson, and Sergeant Michael Winkler) were killed by a PIRA bomb attached to their van in [[Lisburn]]. The bomb was made in such a way so as to ensure it exploded upwards, lowering the risk of collateral damage.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch88.htm#Jun A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1988], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 20 August |[[Ballygawley bus bombing]] – eight British Army soldiers (Blair Bishop, Peter Bullock, Jayson Burfitt, Richard Greener, Alexander Lewis, Mark Norsworthy, Stephen Wilkinson, and Jason Winter) were killed and twenty-eight wounded when the PIRA attacked their bus with a roadside bomb near [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone]].<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch88.htm#Aug A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1988], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 19 October |The British Government introduced the [[1988–94 British broadcasting voice restrictions|broadcasting ban]] on organisations believed to support terrorism – including 11 Loyalist and Republican groups and [[Gerry Adams]]' voice.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4409447.stm The 'broadcast ban' on Sinn Fein], ''BBC'', 5 April 2005; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1989=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 12 February |Republican solicitor [[Pat Finucane]] was assassinated by the [[Ulster Freedom Fighters]]. He was shot dead in front of his wife and two sons.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch89.htm#Feb A Chronology of the Conflict – February 1989], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 September |[[1989 Deal barracks bombing|Deal barracks bombing]] – eleven British military bandsmen were killed by a PIRA bomb at Deal Barracks in [[Kent]], England. |- |valign="top"| October |Twenty-eight members of the British Army ([[Ulster Defence Regiment]]) were arrested on suspicion of leaking security force documents to loyalist paramilitaries.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch89.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1989], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 13 December |[[Attack on Derryard checkpoint]] – using machine guns, grenades and a [[flamethrower]], the PIRA launched an assault on a British Army checkpoint near [[Rosslea]], County Fermanagh, killing two British soldiers (Private James Houston and Lance-Corporal Michael Paterson). Two other soldiers were injured, one more severely than the other.<ref>[http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/northern-ireland-news/family-joins-memorial-service-for-soldiers-murdered-25-years-ago-1-6473393 Family joins memorial service for soldiers murdered 25 years ago], newsletter.co.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
==1990–1999== ===1990=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 9 April |Four British Army (Ulster Defence Regiment) soldiers were killed when the PIRA exploded a landmine under their patrol vehicle in [[Downpatrick]], County Down. The blast was so powerful that the vehicle was hurled into a nearby field. |- |valign="top"| 6 May |[[Operation Conservation]] – the British Army attempted to ambush a PIRA unit in South Armagh, but were counter-ambushed; one British soldier was killed. |- |valign="top"| 20 July |The PIRA bombed the [[London Stock Exchange]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/july/20/newsid_2515000/2515667.stm IRA bombs Stock Exchange], ''BBC On This Day'', 20 July 1990</ref> |- |valign="top"| 24 July |A PIRA landmine attack on an RUC patrol vehicle in Armagh killed three RUC officers (William Hanson, David Sterritt, and Joshua Willis) and a civilian (Sister Catherine Dunne, a Roman Catholic nun from Dublin). |- |valign="top"| 30 July |Conservative MP for [[Eastbourne]], [[Ian Gow]], was assassinated by a PIRA bomb planted in his car. |- |valign="top"| 30 September |Two Catholic civilians (Martin Peake and Karen Reilly) speeding in a stolen vehicle at a checkpoint were shot dead by British Army soldiers in Belfast. |- |valign="top"| 24 October |[[Proxy bomb|Proxy bomb attacks]] – the PIRA launched three "proxy bombs" or "human bombs" at British Army checkpoints. Three men (who were or had been working with the British Army) were tied into cars loaded with explosives and ordered to drive to each checkpoint. Each bomb was detonated by remote control. The first exploded at a checkpoint in Coshquin, killing the driver and five soldiers. The second exploded at a checkpoint in [[Killeen, County Armagh]]; the driver, James McAvoy, narrowly escaped, albeit suffered a broken leg but one soldier (Fusilier Andrew Grundy) was killed and 23 other soldiers were wounded. The third failed to detonate.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch90.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1989], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 November |[[Margaret Thatcher]] resigned as British Prime Minister. |}
===1991=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 3 February |The PIRA launched a "proxy bomb" attack on a British Army ([[Ulster Defense Regiment]]) base in [[Magherafelt]], County Londonderry. The bomb caused major damage to the base and nearby houses, but the driver escaped before it exploded. |- |valign="top"| 7 February |The PIRA launched three [[Downing Street mortar attack|mortar shells at 10 Downing Street]] while the British Cabinet were holding a meeting. The shells landed in a garden. No members of the cabinet were injured, although four people received minor injuries, including two police officers.<ref name=mul/> |- |valign="top"| 3 March |[[1991 Cappagh killings]] – three PIRA volunteers (Malcolm Nugent, Dwayne O'Donnell, and John Quinn) and a Catholic civilian (Thomas Armstrong) were shot dead by the UVF at Boyle's Bar in [[Cappagh, County Tyrone|Cappagh]], County Tyrone. A 21-year-old man was badly wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/chron|title=NI Conflict Archive on the Internet|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> The volunteers arrived in a car as a UVF gang was about to attack the pub. The UVF fired at the car (killing the volunteers) then fired into the pub (killing the civilian) but the alleged target, Brian Arthurs (brother of late PIRA volunteer [[Declan Arthurs]], who was killed at Loughgall) escaped. |- |valign="top"| 28 March |[[1991 Drumbeg killings]] - three [[Irish Catholic]] civilians (including two teenage girls) were shot dead in a mobile shop in a [[Irish Nationalism|Nationalist]] estate in [[Craigavon]] by the [[UVF Mid-Ulster Brigade]] using the covername [[Protestant Action Force]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=28&month=03&year=1991 |title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths |publisher=Cain.ulst.ac.uk |date=1991-03-28 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 29 April |The [[Combined Loyalist Military Command]] (CLMC) (acting on behalf of all loyalist paramilitaries) announced a ceasefire lasting until 4 July. This was to coincide with political talks between the four main parties (the Brooke-Mayhew talks).{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 31 May |[[Glenanne barracks bombing]] – the PIRA launched a large truck bomb attack on a British Army (Ulster Defence Regiment) base in County Armagh. Three soldiers (Lance Corporal Robert Crozier and Privates Paul Blakely and Sydney Hamilton) were killed; ten soldiers and four civilians were wounded. The blast left a deep crater and it could be heard over 30 miles away. Most of the UDR base was destroyed by the blast and the fire that followed. It was one of the largest bombs detonated during the Troubles in Northern Ireland. |- |valign="top"| 3 June |[[Coagh ambush]] – the SAS shot dead three PIRA volunteers (Tony Doris, Lawrence McNally and Michael "Pete" Ryan) as they traveled in a car through [[Coagh]], County Tyrone. The car burst into flames. {{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
===1992=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 17 January |[[Teebane bombing]] – a PIRA landmine killed eight Protestant men and wounded six others at Teebane Crossroads near [[Cookstown]], County Tyrone. The men had been working for the British Army at a base in Omagh and were returning home on a minibus. The PIRA said that the men were legitimate targets because they had been "[[collaborationism|collaborating]]" with the "forces of occupation". Shortly thereafter, [[Peter Brooke]] (Secretary of State for Northern Ireland) appeared on the Irish [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]] ''Late Late Show'' and was persuaded to sing "[[Oh My Darling, Clementine]]". Unionists accused him of gross insensitivity for agreeing to do so. |- |valign="top"| 4 February |Allen Moore, a RUC officer from [[Comber]], reportedly distraught by the killing of a colleague, Constable Norman Spratt, walked into a Belfast [[Sinn Féin]] office and shot dead two Sinn Féin activists, Patrick Loughran (61) and Patrick McBride (aged 40), and one civilian, Michael O'Dwyer (aged 24), all Catholics. Moore drove away from the scene and later shot himself.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/ruc-man-tells-of-call-from-colleague-inquest-told-of-threats-made-on-phone-2322306.html RUC man tells of call from colleague - inquest told of threats made on phone], independent.co.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 5 February |[[Sean Graham bookmakers' shooting]] – the UDA, using the covername "Ulster Freedom Fighters" (UFF), claimed responsibility for a gun attack on a bookmaker's shop on Lower Ormeau Road, Belfast. Five Catholic men and boys were killed (Christy Doherty, Jack Duffin, James Kennedy, Peter Magee, and William McManus). Nine others were wounded, one critically. This was claimed as retaliation for the Teebane bombing on 17 January 1992.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch92.htm#Feb A Chronology of the Conflict – February 1992], CAIN.ulst.ac.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> In November 1992, the UDA carried out another attack on a betting shop in Belfast, killing three Catholic civilians and wounding thirteen. |- |valign="top"| 16 February |[[Clonoe ambush]] – a PIRA unit attacked [[Coalisland]] RUC base in County Tyrone using a [[heavy machine gun]] mounted on the back of a stolen lorry. Following the attack, the British Army ambushed the unit in a graveyard. Four PIRA volunteers (Peter Clancy, Kevin Barry O'Donnell, Seán O'Farrell, and Patrick Vincent) were killed and two were wounded but escaped.<ref>{{cite book|last=O'Brien|first=Brendan|authorlink=Brendan O'Brien (Irish journalist)|title=The Long War: The IRA and Sinn Féin|publisher=O'Brien Press|year=1999|pages=232–235|isbn=0-86278-606-1}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 10 April |The PIRA exploded a truck bomb at the [[Baltic Exchange]] in London. Despite a telephoned warning, three civilians were killed. The bomb caused £800 million worth of damage. |- |valign="top"| 1 May |[[Attack on Cloghoge checkpoint]] – the PIRA, using a van modified to run on railway tracks, launched an elaborate bomb attack on a British Army checkpoint in South Armagh. The checkpoint was obliterated. One soldier (Fusilier Andrew Grundy) was killed and 23 wounded. |- |valign="top"| 17 May |[[Coalisland riots (1992)|Coalisland riots]] – after a PIRA bomb attack on a British Army patrol near [[Cappagh, County Tyrone]], in which a soldier lost his legs, British soldiers raided two public houses in [[Coalisland]] and caused considerable damage. This led to a fist-fight between the soldiers and locals. Shortly thereafter, another group of British soldiers arrived and fired on a crowd of civilians, wounding seven.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch92.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1992], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 28 August |The PIRA's "[[South Armagh Sniper (1990–1997)|South Armagh snipers]]" undertook their first successful operation, when a British Army soldier (Private Paul Turner) was shot dead on patrol in Crossmaglen, County Armagh. |- |valign="top"| 23 September |The PIRA exploded a 2000&nbsp;lb bomb at the Northern Ireland [[Crime lab|Forensic Science Laboratory]] in South Belfast. The laboratory was obliterated, seven hundred houses were damaged, and 20 people were injured. The explosion could be heard from over 16&nbsp;km away. It was one of the largest bombs to be detonated during the Troubles in Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch92.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – September 1992], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1993=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 26 February |[[Warrington bomb attacks]] – A bomb exploded at a gas storage facility in Warrington. It caused extensive damage but no injuries. While fleeing the scene, the bombers shot and injured a police officer and two of them were then caught after a high-speed car chase. |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 20 March |[[Warrington bomb attacks]] – after a telephoned warning, the PIRA exploded two bombs in Warrington, [[Cheshire]], England. Two children (Johnathan Ball and Tim Parry) were killed and fifty-six people were wounded. There were widespread protests in Britain and Ireland following the deaths. |- |valign="top"| 25 March |[[Castlerock killings]] – the UDA, using the covername "Ulster Freedom Fighters" (UFF), claimed responsibility for shooting dead four Catholic civilians and a PIRA volunteer at a building site in [[Castlerock]], County Londonderry. Later in the day it claimed responsibility for shooting dead another Catholic civilian in Belfast.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch93.htm#Mar A Chronology of the Conflict – March 1993], CAIN.ulst.ac.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 24 April |[[1993 Bishopsgate bombing|Bishopsgate bombing]] – after a telephoned warning, the PIRA exploded a large bomb at [[Bishopsgate]], London. It killed one civilian, wounded thirty others, and caused an estimated £350 million in damage. |- |valign="top"| 23 October |[[Shankill Road bombing]] – eight civilians,one PIRA volunteer were killed when a PIRA bomb prematurely exploded at a fish shop on [[Shankill Road]], Belfast. The PIRA's intended target was a meeting of loyalist paramilitary leaders, which was scheduled to take place in a room above the shop. However, unbeknownst to the PIRA, the meeting had been re-scheduled. |- |valign="top"| 30 October |[[Greysteel massacre]] – the UDA, using the covername "Ulster Freedom Fighters" (UFF), claimed responsibility for a gun attack on the Rising Sun Bar in [[Greysteel]], County Londonderry. Eight civilians (six Catholic, two Protestant) were killed and twelve wounded. One gunman yelled "[[trick or treat]]!" before he fired into the crowded room; a reference to the [[Halloween]] party taking place. The UFF claimed that it had attacked the "nationalist electorate" in revenge for the Shankill Road bombing.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch93.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1993], CAIN.ulst.ac.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1994=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| January''' |The [[Censorship in the Republic of Ireland#The Troubles|broadcasting ban]] on Sinn Féin was lifted in the Republic of Ireland. |- |valign="top"| March |The PIRA carried out a mortar attack on [[Heathrow Airport]], London. Further attacks were carried out later in the month, but on each occasion the mortars failed to explode. |- |valign="top"| 21 May |IRA volunteer Martin Doherty shot dead in an attempted bombing by the UVF of the Widow Scallans pub in Dublin, which was hosting a republican meeting. |- |valign="top"| 2 June |Twenty-nine people, including ten senior RUC officers, died during the [[1994 Scotland RAF Chinook crash]] at [[Mull of Kintyre]], Scotland. They were travelling from Belfast to a security conference in [[Inverness]]. |- |valign="top"| 16 June |[[1994 Shankill Road killings]]: The army shot dead UVF member Trevor king as he was on his way back from a mission. |- |valign="top"| 18 June |[[Loughinisland massacre]] – the UVF shot dead six Catholic civilians (Eamon Byrne, Barney Greene, Malcolm Jenkinson, Daniel McCreanor, Patrick O'Hare, and Adrian Rogan) and wounded five others during a gun attack on a pub in [[Loughinisland]], County Down.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch94.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1994], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 31 August |The Provisional Irish Republican Army (PIRA) issued a statement which announced a complete cessation of military activities.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch94.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – August 1994], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> This ceasefire was broken less than two years later. |- |valign="top"| 16 September |The [[1988–94 British broadcasting voice restrictions|broadcasting ban]] was lifted in the UK. |- |valign="top"| 13 October |The [[Combined Loyalist Military Command]] (CLMC) issued a statement which announced a ceasefire on behalf of all loyalist paramilitaries. The statement noted that "The permanence of our cease-fire will be completely dependent upon the continued cessation of all nationalist/republican violence".<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch94.htm A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1994], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1995=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| January |A delegation from Sinn Féin met with officials from the Northern Ireland Office. |- |valign="top"| February |The British and Irish governments released the Joint Framework document. |- |valign="top"| March |Gerry Adams attended a reception held by Bill Clinton at the White House. |- |valign="top"| July |[[Lee Clegg]], a British Army paratrooper, was released from prison on the orders of Secretary of State [[Patrick Mayhew]]. Clegg had been jailed in 1993, for the murder of Catholic teenager Karen Reilly. |- |valign="top"| September |[[David Trimble]] was elected as the leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]], following the resignation of [[James Molyneaux]]. |}
===1996=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 9 February |[[1996 Docklands bombing|London Docklands bombing]] – after a telephoned warning, the PIRA bombed the [[London Docklands|Docklands]] in London. The bomb killed two civilians (Inam Bashir and John Jeffries) and injured 39 others. It brought an end to the ceasefire after 17 months and 9 days. |- |valign="top"| 10 June |Political talks at Stormont began without Sinn Féin.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch96.htm#Jun A Chronology of the Conflict – June 1996], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 15 June |[[1996 Manchester bombing|Manchester bombing]] – after a telephoned warning, the PIRA exploded a bomb in [[Manchester]], England. It destroyed a large part of the city centre and injured over 200 people. To date, it is the largest bomb to be detonated on the British mainland since the Second World War. There were no fatalities.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| July |[[Drumcree conflict]] – the RUC decided to block the annual Orange Order march through the nationalist Garvaghy area of Portadown. In response, loyalist protestors attacked the RUC and blocked hundreds of roads across Northern Ireland. Eventually, the RUC allowed the march to continue, leading to serious rioting by nationalists across Northern Ireland.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch96.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1996], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 7 October |The Provisional IRA [[Thiepval barracks bombing|exploded two bombs at the British Army HQ]] in [[Thiepval Barracks]], Lisburn. A British soldier, Warrant Officer James Bradwell, died four days later of his wounds. 31 other people were wounded.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch96.htm#Oct A Chronology of the Conflict – October 1996], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |}
===1997=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 12 February |A PIRA sniper shot dead a British soldier (Lance Bombardier Stephen Restorick) manning a checkpoint in Bessbrook, County Armagh. He was the last British soldier to be killed during [[Operation Banner]]. |- |valign="top"| 5 April |The [[Grand National]] horse race was cancelled, and [[Aintree Racecourse]] evacuated following a hoax bomb warning from the PIRA. The race was eventually run several days later, 7 April, without disruption.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 1 May |[[Tony Blair]] becomes UK Prime Minister after winning a landslide victory ending 18 years of Conservative rule. |- |valign="top"| June |[[Sinn Féin]] won its first ever seats in [[Dáil Éireann]] (Irish Parliament) |- |valign="top"|16 June |The PIRA shot dead two RUC officers (John Graham and David Johnston) on patrol, Church Walk, Lurgan, County Armagh. They were the last RUC officers killed before the signing of the Belfast Agreement (see below). |- |valign="top"| 6–9 July |[[Drumcree conflict]] – to ensure the Orange Order march could continue, the security forces sealed-off the nationalist Garvaghy area of [[Portadown]]. This sparked [[1997 nationalist riots in Northern Ireland|serious rioting in Portadown and across nationalist areas in Northern Ireland]]. After four days, the RUC released figures which showed that there had been 60 RUC officers injured; 56 civilians injured; 117 people arrested; 2,500 [[plastic bullet]]s fired; 815 attacks on the security forces; 1,506 petrol bombs thrown; and 402 hijackings.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch97.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1997], ''CAIN Web Service''</ref> This was the last time that the Orange Order's parade through nationalist areas around Drumcree was permitted by the authorities.<ref>Daugherty Rasnic, Carol (2003). ''Northern Ireland: can Sean and John live in peace?'' Brandylane Publishers Inc, p. 54; {{ISBN|1-883911-55-9}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 20 July |The PIRA renewed its ceasefire. |- |valign="top"| September |Sinn Féin signed the [[Mitchell Principles]]. Multi-party talks resumed. |- |valign="top"| 27 December |INLA prisoners shot dead [[Loyalist Volunteer Force]] (LVF) leader and fellow prisoner [[Billy Wright (loyalist)|Billy Wright]] inside the maximum-security Maze Prison. The LVF launched a number of revenge attacks over the following weeks.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} |}
===1998=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 10 April |After two years of intensive talks, the [[Belfast Agreement]] (also known as the 'Stormont Agreement' or 'Good Friday Agreement') was signed at [[Parliament Buildings (Northern Ireland)|Stormont]] in Belfast. |- |valign="top"| 15 May |The [[Loyalist Volunteer Force]] (LVF) declared an "unequivocal ceasefire". The group hoped this would encourage people to vote against the Belfast Agreement.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch98.htm#May A Chronology of the Conflict – May 1998], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 May |Two referendums were held on the Belfast Agreement, [[Northern Ireland Belfast Agreement referendum, 1998|one in Northern Ireland]] and [[Nineteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|one in the Republic of Ireland]]. In Northern Ireland the vote was 71.2% in favour, in the Republic of Ireland the vote was 94.39% in favour.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/northern_ireland/understanding/events/good_friday.stm Good Friday Agreement], BBC.co.uk; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 25 June |[[Northern Ireland Assembly election, 1998|Northern Ireland Assembly elections]] were held. [[David Trimble]] was elected First Minister. [[Seamus Mallon]] was elected deputy. |- |valign="top"| 5–12 July |[[Drumcree conflict]] – the annual Orange Order march was prevented from marching through the nationalist Garvaghy area of Portadown. Security forces and about 10,000 loyalists began a standoff at Drumcree church. During this time, loyalists launched 550 attacks on the security forces and numerous attacks on Catholic civilians. On 12 July, three children were burnt to death in a loyalist petrol bomb attack. This incident brought an end to the standoff.<ref>[http://www.cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch98.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 1998], ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 15 August |[[Omagh bombing]] – a [[dissident republican]] group calling itself the [[Real Irish Republican Army|Real IRA]] exploded a bomb in [[Omagh]], County Tyrone. It killed twenty-nine civilians (one of whom was pregnant with twins), making it the worst single bombing of the Troubles, in terms of civilian life lost.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 22 August |The [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA) declared a ceasefire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/events/northern_ireland/latest_news/156435.stm|title=BBC News – UK and Ireland welcome INLA ceasefire|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 16 October |John Hume and David Trimble jointly awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/1998/press.html|title=Press Release - Nobel Peace Prize 1998|publisher=Nobel Media AB|date=2014|website=NobelPrize.org|accessdate=13 October 2015}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 1998 |Considered by many as the end of the troubles.<ref name="Ireland 1999, page 221"/><ref name="Northern Ireland Conflict' page 250"/><ref>Aughey, A. ''The Politics of Northern Ireland: Beyond the Belfast Agreement'', p. 7; {{ISBN|978-0-415-32788-6}}</ref> Violence nonetheless continues on a small-scale basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/sutton/index.html|title=Draft List of Deaths Related to the Conflict. 2002– |accessdate=31 July 2008}}</ref> |}
===1999=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 27 January |Former IRA volunteer and [[Supergrass (informer)|supergrass]] [[Eamon Collins]] was found dead near [[Newry]], County Down. The South Armagh IRA were believed to have been responsible. |- |valign="top"| 15 March |Solicitor [[Rosemary Nelson]], who had represented the Garvaghy residents in the Drumcree dispute, was assassinated by a booby trapped car bomb in [[Lurgan]], County Armagh. A loyalist group, [[Red Hand Defenders]], claimed responsibility.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} |- |valign="top"| 8 August |The INLA and its political wing the [[Irish Republican Socialist Party|IRSP]] stated that "There is no political or moral argument to justify a resumption of the campaign".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/414555.stm|title=BBC News – INLA 'declares war is over'|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 1 December |[[Direct rule over Northern Ireland|Direct rule]] officially ended as power was handed over to the Northern Ireland Assembly. |}
==2000–2009== ===2000=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 11 February |Direct rule was reinstated and the Northern Ireland Assembly suspended by new [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]] [[Peter Mandelson]], citing insufficient progress on decommissioning.<ref name=bbcnov11>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/3259873.stm Timeline: Northern Ireland Assembly], BBC.co.uk, 11 November 2003.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 27 March |The [[Bloody Sunday Inquiry]] began in Derry. It is the biggest [[public inquiry]] in British history.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/nov/22/bloodysunday.northernireland The Bloody Sunday inquiry], Guardian.co.uk, 22 November 2004.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 29 May |Devolution was restored to the Northern Ireland Assembly.<ref name=bbcnov11/> |- |valign="top"| 2–12 July |[[Drumcree conflict]] – the annual Orange Order parade was banned from marching through the nationalist Garvaghy area of Portadown. The security forces erected large barricades to prevent loyalists from entering the area. About 2,000 British soldiers were deployed to keep order. During the standoff at Drumcree Church, loyalists continually launched missiles at the security forces.<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch00.htm#Jul A Chronology of the Conflict – July 2000] ''CAIN Web Service''; accessed 23 October 2015.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 28 July |The final prisoners were released from the Maze Prison, under the conditions of the Good Friday Agreement.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/the-maze-gives-up-its-terrorists-for-the-final-time-706369.html The Maze gives up its terrorists for the final time], Independent.co.uk, 28 July 2000.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 21 September |The [[Real IRA]] (RIRA) fired a [[RPG-22|rocket propelled grenade]] at [[SIS Building|MI6 headquarters]] in London, causing superficial damage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Security tight in London in wake of MI6 attack|url=http://rte.ie/news/2000/0921/dissidents.html|publisher=''[[RTÉ]]''|date=21 September 2000|accessdate=3 May 2007}}</ref><ref name="MI6">Boyne, p. 384.</ref> |}
===2001=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 4 March |[[4 March 2001 BBC bombing|BBC bombing]] – a Real IRA bomb exploded outside [[BBC Television Centre]], causing some damage to the building. |- |valign="top"| 19 June |[[Holy Cross dispute]] – RUC officers had to protect pupils and parents at Holy Cross Catholic Girls' School in Belfast, following attacks from loyalist protesters. The attacks resumed in September, following the school summer holidays, before subsiding in January 2002.<ref>[http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2004/12/05/story742.asp Haunting tale of a school under siege], ''The Sunday Business Post'', 5 December 2004.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 11–13 July |[[July 2001 Belfast riots]] - The worst rioting for several years took place in Belfast.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2001/sep/19/northernireland.derekbrown Northern Ireland timeline: May 2000 to September 2001], Guardian.co.uk, 19 September 2001.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 3 August |[[3 August 2001 Ealing bombing|Ealing bombing]] – a Real IRA car bomb injured seven civilians in [[Ealing]], west [[London]]. |- |valign="top"| 23 October |The Provisional IRA began decommissioning of its weaponry.<ref>[http://premium.edition.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/europe/10/23/ira.announce/index.html IRA begins disarming], CNN.com, 23 October 2001.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 4 November |The RUC was replaced by the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]] (PSNI). Recruits were recruited on the basis of 50% Catholic, 50% Protestant.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/1636780.stm 'New era' as NI police change name], BBC.co.uk, 4 November 2001.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 11 November |[[November 2001 Belfast riots]] - Fierce riots take place in Belfast. One teenager is killed. |- |valign="top"| 9 December |[[2001 South Armagh attacks]] - Republicans attack police and soldiers at two watchtowers in County Armagh. |}
===2002=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 5 May |[[May 2002 Belfast riots]] |- |valign="top"| 31 May-7 June |[[2002 Short Strand clashes]] - major violence near a Catholic enclave in Belfast. |}
===2005=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 12 July |Police were attacked with blast and petrol bombs during rioting in the [[Ardoyne]] area of Belfast, following an [[Orange Order]] parade. Eighty police officers were injured and several people were arrested.<ref>{{cite news|title=80 officers injured during riot|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4677401.stm|publisher=BBC|date=13 July 2005}}</ref> |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 28 July |The PIRA issued a statement declaring the end of its armed campaign and will verifiably put its weapons beyond use.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full text: IRA statement|url=https://www.theguardian.com/Northern_Ireland/Story/0,,1537996,00.html|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 July 2005|accessdate=17 March 2007|location=London, UK}}</ref> |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 26 September |International weapons inspectors issue a statement confirming the full decommissioning of the PIRA's weaponry.<ref>{{cite news|title=IRA 'has destroyed all its arms'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4283444.stm|publisher=BBC.co.uk|date=26 September 2005|accessdate=6 April 2007}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 11–12 September |[[2005 Belfast riots]] - Following the rerouting of a controversial Orange Order Parade, rioting broke out in Belfast on a scale not seen for many years,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4233850.stm Violent clashes erupt in Belfast], BBC.co.uk, 11 September 2005.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/sep/12/northernireland 50 police officers injured in Belfast riots], Guardian.co.uk, 12 September 2005.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 30 October |The [[Loyalist Volunteer Force]] (LVF) instructed its forces to "stand down". |}
===2006=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 25 February |[[2006 Dublin riots]] |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 24 November |[[Michael Stone (loyalist paramilitary)|Michael Stone]] was arrested for breaking into the Stormont parliament buildings while armed. He would receive 16 years [[imprisonment]] for attempting to murder [[Martin McGuinness]] and [[Gerry Adams]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ireland/3459298/Michael-Stone-guilty-of-attempted-murder-of-Gerry-Adams-and-Martin-McGuinness.html "Michael Stone guilty of attempted murder of Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness"], ''Telegraph'', 14 November 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/dec/08/michael-stone-sentence Loyalist killer Michael Stone jailed for 16 years], Guardian.co.uk, 8 December 2008.</ref> |}
===2007=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 7 March | [[Northern Ireland Assembly election, 2007|Elections to the Northern Ireland Assembly]] took place. |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 26 March | [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] leader, [[Ian Paisley]] and [[Sinn Féin]] leader, [[Gerry Adams]] meet face-to-face for the first time, and the two come to an agreement regarding the return of the power-sharing executive in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/6494599.stm|work=BBC News|title=NI deal struck in historic talks|date=26 March 2007|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 3 May | The UVF and RHC issued a statement declaring an end to its armed campaign. The statement noted that they would retain their weapons but put them "beyond reach".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6618365.stm|title=BBC News – UVF Statement|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6618371.stm|title=BBC News – Statement Released|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 8 May | The new [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] met and the new [[Northern Ireland Executive]] was formed. |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 31 July | The British military's campaign in Northern Ireland (codenamed [[Operation Banner]]) officially ends. |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 11 November | The UDA issued a statement declaring an end to its armed campaign. The statement noted that they would retain their weapons but put them "beyond use".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/7089310.stm|title=UFF given the order to stand down|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |}
===2008=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 16 August |The [[Continuity IRA]] (CIRA) fired a [[rocket-propelled grenade]] at a police patrol in [[Lisnaskea]], County Fermanagh. Three officers required hospital treatment.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2008/aug/18/republican.rocket.attack Dissident republicans in rocket attack on police in Northern Ireland], guardian.co.uk, 18 August 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www3.u.tv/news/localNews/index.asp?sel=1&sel2=1&local=1&id=90592&pt=n Calls for urgent inquiry into dissident access to semtex], u.tv/news, 19 August 2008.</ref> |- |valign="top"| 25 August |Riots erupted in [[Craigavon]], during which a number of vehicles were hijacked and shots were fired. The Independent Monitoring Commission blamed the CIRA for orchestrating the violence.<ref>[http://www.independentmonitoringcommission.org/documents/uploads/Twentieth%20Report.pdf Twentieth Report Of The Independent Monitoring Commission] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218015532/http://www.independentmonitoringcommission.org/documents/uploads/Twentieth%20Report.pdf |date=18 December 2008 }} (PDF), independentmonitoringcommission.org; accessed 17 August 2016.</ref> |}
===2009=== {|width=100%|} | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 7 March |Two British Army soldiers (Patrick Azimkar and Mark Quinsey) were shot dead and two others were seriously injured during a [[2009 Massereene Barracks shooting|gun attack at Massereene Barracks]] in [[County Antrim]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7931260.stm How the barracks attack unfolded], bbc.co.uk, 9 March 2009.</ref> The dissident [[Real IRA]] (RIRA) claimed responsibility. These were the first British military fatalities in Northern Ireland since 1997.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0308/massereene.html Real IRA claims responsibility for attack], ''RTÉ News'', 8 March 2009</ref> |- |valign="top"| 9 March |A Catholic police officer (formerly RUC, then PSNI), Stephen Carroll, was shot dead in [[Craigavon]], [[County Armagh]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7933990.stm Police officer shot dead in town], BBC.co.uk, 10 March 2009.</ref> The [[Continuity Irish Republican Army|CIRA]] claimed responsibility. This was the first police fatality in Northern Ireland since 1998.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0310/craigavon.html Two men held over PSNI murder] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090311135830/http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0310/craigavon.html |date=11 March 2009 }}, rte.ie, 10 March 2009</ref> Police were petrol bombed when arrests were made. {{Clarify|date=October 2015}} |- |valign="top"| 27 June |It was announced that the [[Ulster Volunteer Force (1966)|Ulster Volunteer Force]] (UVF) and the [[Red Hand Commando]] (RHC) had decommissioned their weapons. |- |valign="top"| 11 October |The [[Irish National Liberation Army|INLA]] formally vow to pursue its aims through peaceful political means, saying their "armed struggle is over".{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
==2010 onward== ===2010=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"| 6 January |It was announced that the [[Ulster Defence Association]] (UDA) had decommissioned its weapons in front of independent witnesses.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8442683.stm|work=BBC News|title=UDA confirm guns decommissioned|date=6 January 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 6 February |It was announced that the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA) had decommissioned its weapons in front of independent witnesses.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8503544.stm|work=BBC News|title=INLA confirms disposal of weapons|date=8 February 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 9 February |The [[Independent International Commission on Decommissioning]] stood down.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8506659.stm|work=BBC News|title=Decommissioning body stands down|date=9 February 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 22 February |The RIRA were blamed for detonating a car bomb outside a courthouse in Newry, heavily damaging the guard hut. This was the first successful car bomb attack in Northern Ireland since 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title='Sheer miracle' that Newry court bomb did not kill anybody|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8529884.stm|publisher=BBC.co.uk|date=23 February 2010|accessdate=24 February 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 12 April |A group calling itself [[Óglaigh na hÉireann (Real IRA splinter group)|Óglaigh na hÉireann]] claimed responsibility for detonating a car bomb outside the [[MI5]] headquarters at Palace Barracks in [[Holywood]], County Down.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8614723.stm|work=BBC News|title=Real IRA admits NI MI5 base bomb|date=12 April 2010|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 23 April |A car bomb exploded outside a PSNI station in [[Newtownhamilton]], County Armagh.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/8638902.stm|work=BBC News|title=Car bomb explodes outside County Armagh police station|date=23 April 2010|accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 28 May |The UVF were blamed for shooting dead former Red Hand Commando member Bobby Moffett in broad daylight on Shankill Road, Belfast. The killing put the UVF's claims of weapons decommissioning and commitment to peace under serious scrutiny.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rowan|first=Brian|title=Bobby Moffett shooting makes a mockery of decommissioning|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/bobby-moffett-shooting-makes-a-mockery-of-decommissioning-14826077.html|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph|date=31 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Madden|first=Anne|title=Shankill Road turns back on UVF|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/local-national/shankill-road-turns-back-on-uvf-14831338.html|newspaper=Belfast Telegraph|date=5 June 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 11–15 July |[[2010 Northern Ireland riots]] |- |valign="top"| 3 August |[[Óglaigh na hÉireann (Real IRA splinter group)|Óglaigh na hÉireann]] claimed responsibility for detonating a 200&nbsp;lb car bomb outside Strand Road PSNI station in Derry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-10853360|work=BBC News|title= 200lb of explosives in Derry car bomb|date=3 August 2010|accessdate=3 August 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 4 October |The RIRA claimed responsibility for detonating a car bomb near the [[Ulster Bank]] on Culmore Road, Derry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-foyle-west-11473586|work=BBC News|title=Real IRA claims Derry car bomb attack|date=4 October 2010|accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> |- |valign="top"| 6 November |Three PSNI officers were injured after a grenade was thrown at them on Shaw's Road, Belfast. Óglaigh na hÉireann claimed responsibility.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-11703535|work=BBC News|title=Three police hurt in West Belfast bomb attack|date=6 November 2010|accessdate=7 November 2010}}</ref> |}
===2011=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|2 April |[[Ronan Kerr]], a 25-year-old Catholic PSNI officer, was killed after a bomb exploded under his car in Omagh, County Tyrone. The Real IRA claimed responsibility.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/booby-trap-bomb-kills-policeman-in-northern-ireland-2260912.html|work=The Independent|title=Booby trap bomb kills policeman in Northern Ireland|date=2 April 2011|accessdate=3 April 2011}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|17–20 May |[[Queen Elizabeth II's visit to the Republic of Ireland]]. |- |valign="top"|May–July |Irish dissident republicans at Roe House, [[Maghaberry (HM Prison)|Maghaberry Prison]] took part in a [[dirty protest]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-20422820 Prisoners in Roe House at Maghaberry end dirty protest], bbc.com; accessed 25 December 2016.</ref> |- |valign="top"|June–July |[[2011 Northern Ireland riots]] |}
===2012=== {|width=100%|} | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|27 June |Queen Elizabeth II shakes hands with Northern Irish politicians including [[Martin McGuinness]]. |- |valign="top"|12 July |[[2012 North Belfast riots]] – there was rioting in the Ardoyne area of Belfast following the Orange Order's Twelfth marches. Up to 20 PSNI officers were injured and a number of shots were fired by republicans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-18823292|title=Owen Paterson in call over Northern Ireland parades|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|26 July |The Real IRA announced that it was merging with [[Republican Action Against Drugs]] and other independent dissident republican groups.<ref>{{cite news|last=McDonald|first=Henry|title=Republican dissidents join forces to form a new IRA|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jul/26/ira-northern-ireland-dissident-republican-groups|newspaper=The Guardian|date=26 July 2012}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|2–4 September |[[2012 North Belfast riots]] – loyalists attack a republican parade organized by [[Republican Network for Unity]] in north Belfast, sparking three nights of rioting between nationalists and loyalists in the area of Carlisle Circus. More than 60 PSNI officers were injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-19457015|title=Forty-seven PSNI officers are injured in Belfast parade clashes|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/News/Ten-officers-injured-in-parade-disorder/478c832c-1fe7-4027-aa6a-afd08da2b5db|title=26 officers hurt in parade disorder|work=u.tv|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McDonald|first=Henry|title=Belfast riots leave 13 police officers injured|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/sep/02/belfast-riots-police-officers-injured?newsfeed=true|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 September 2012}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|1 November |A [[Northern Ireland Prison Service|Prison Officer]], David Black, was shot dead on the [[M1 motorway (Northern Ireland)|M1 motorway]] near [[Craigavon]] while driving to work. The shots were fired from another car, which drove alongside. The Real IRA<!--all dissident republican groups call themselves "the IRA" in some form or another; this was claimed by the recently restructured group that *we* call the RIRA to distinguish it from the others--> claimed responsibility and said it was a response to the treatment of republican prisoners holding a [[dirty protest]] at [[HM Prison Maghaberry|Maghaberry Prison]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-20296702 "David Black murder: New 'IRA' group claims it murdered prison officer"]. BBC News, 12 November 2012.</ref> He was the first Prison Officer to be killed since 1993. |- |valign="top"|4 December |[[Belfast City Hall flag protests]]: [[Belfast City Council]] votes to only fly the [[Union Jack]] from [[Belfast City Hall]] on designated days. Since 1906, it had been flown every day of the year. This sparked protests by loyalists throughout Northern Ireland, some of which became violent. The protests and rioting continued into 2013.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} |}
===2013=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|January |[[Belfast City Hall flag protests]]: Numerous riots occur throughout the month in Belfast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-21020296 |title=Union flag dispute: Riot breaks out in east Belfast - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|12-17 July |[[2013 Belfast riots]]: Rioting by loyalists occurred across Belfast and across of Northern Ireland after an Orange Order parade was prevented by the PSNI from passing the nationalist Ardoyne shop fronts in North Belfast during The Twelfth celebrations, in accordance with a Parades Commission ruling. During which loyalists attacked with petrol bombs, [[blast bomb]]s and even reportedly ceremonial swords. There were clashes between loyalist and nationalist crowds. 71 PSNI officers including 3 mutual aid officers from Britain were injured in the days of rioting, and during disorder on 12 July DUP MP [[Nigel Dodds]] was injured after he was knocked unconscious by a brick thrown by loyalists. 62 people involved in the rioting were arrested across Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/news/32-police-hurt-in-shameful-rioting/ff9dfedf-2377-41f0-9f84-8fb9237cd13e|title=32 police hurt in 'shameful' rioting|work=u.tv|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/news/DUP-MP-injured-in-north-Belfast-riot/04636d71-a731-4e62-9e72-db7207ef9cba|title=DUP MP injured in north Belfast riot|work=u.tv|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/News/Petrol-bombs-thrown-in-east-Belfast/980dcb27-fb56-4e2e-8a0b-9e1bb82aa392|title=Petrol bombs thrown in east Belfast|work=u.tv|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/utvplayer/video.aspx?vidid=152472&chapid=127317|title=UTV Player - Home|work=UTV Player|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u.tv/News/Boy-12-among-NI-riot-arrests/88180bcb-9232-4a44-9f74-a8032285128e|title=Boy, 12, among NI riot arrests|work=u.tv|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|9 August |[[2013 Belfast riots]]: Rioting between loyalists and nationalists during a dissident republican march through Belfast city centre. |}
===2015=== {|width=100% | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|12-15 July |Several days of rioting in north Belfast.<ref>[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/twelfth-2015-third-night-of-rioting-in-north-belfast-loyalists-trash-retirement-home-wreck-own-community-31381325.html]{{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref> |}
===2016=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|4 March |A prison officer (Adrian Ismay) died from a heart attack in a hospital on 4 March 2016. He had been seriously wounded by a booby-trap bomb which detonated under his van on Hillsborough Drive, East Belfast 11 days earlier. These wounds were directly responsible for the heart attack that killed him. The "New IRA" claimed responsibility and said it was a response to the alleged mistreatment of republican prisoners at [[HM Prison Maghaberry|Maghaberry Prison]]. It added that the officer was targeted because he trained prison officers at Maghaberry.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-35742097 "Belfast bomb: Dissident republicans 'new IRA' claim prison officer attack"], BBC.co.uk, 7 March 2016.</ref> |}
===2017=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|22 January |A police officer is shot and injured by a dissident republican in Crumlin Road, Belfast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-38716584 |title=Belfast policeman injured during gunfire at filling station - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |}
===2018=== {|width=100% |- | style="width:100px; vertical-align:top;"|23 January |The leadership of Óglaigh na hÉireann issued a statement declaring a ceasefire. This was confirmed at a press conference in Belfast called by two prominent trade unionists and Eamon O Cuiv TD. The ceasefire was welcomed by Sinn Féin leader Gerry Adams and Taniste Simon Coveney.<ref>{{cite web|author=More by Tommie Gorman Northern Editor |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ulster/2018/0123/935296-dissident-ceasefire-announcement/ |title=IRA dissident splinter group announces ceasefire |publisher=Rte.ie |date=2018-01-23 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |- |valign="top"|2 April |Rioting and violence break out following an illegal dissident republican march in Londonderry. Five were arrested.<ref>[https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/940459/northern-ireland-riots-illegal-march-easter-parade-londonderry]{{dead link|date=September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=4 April 2018 at 3:14pm |url=http://www.itv.com/news/utv/2018-04-04/five-arrested-over-easter-monday-disorder-in-derry/ |title=Five arrested over Easter Monday disorder in Derry &#124; UTV - ITV News |publisher=Itv.com |date=2018-04-04 |accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> |}
